<P>Here is the brief of the United States filed December 12, 1995 arguing that the death penalty is constitutional and that the Attorney General acted within the scope of her discretion in seeking the death penalty against McVeigh and Nichols.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<PRE>
Here is the brief of the United States filed December 12, 1995 arguing that the death penalty is constitutional and that the Attorney General acted within the scope of her discretion in seeking the death penalty against McViegh and Nichols.
 
IN THE UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT FOR THE 
WESTERN DISTRICT OF OKLAHOMA  
 
UNITED STATES OF AMERICA,           
Plaintiff,                                                      
                                                                    
vs.                                   Case No. CR-95-110-A 
                    
TIMOTHY JAMES McVEIGH                  
and TERRY LYNN NICHOLS                         
Defendants.                                                 
 
 
BRIEF OF THE UNITED STATES IN OPPOSITION TO 
DEFENDANTS' MOTIONS TO STRIKE THE NOTICES OF 
INTENT TO SEEK THE DEATH PENALTY  
On October 20, 1995, pursuant to 18 U.S.C. 3593(a), the United 
States filed separate notices of its intention to seek the death 
penalty in the event defendants were convicted on any of the 
eleven capital counts charged in the indictment. The separate 
notices apprised defendants McVeigh and Nichols of the five 
statutory aggravating factors, four non-statutory aggravating 
factors, and four mental culpability factors on which the 
government intended to rely at a bifurcated capital sentencing 
hearing.    
 
In moving to strike the notices, defendants challenge 1) the 
constitutionality of the federal death penalty statute,  2)  the 
manner in which the government instituted the capital proceedings 
against them, and 3) the validity of all the statutory and non- 
statutory  aggravating  factors  alleged  in  the  death  notices. 
Defendants' claims, many of the which have been rejected by 
courts construing similar provisions and procedures contained in 
the federal death penalty statute pertaining to drug-related murders 
(21 U.S.C. 848(e), et sea.), fail in all respects.  
 
I.  THE FEDERAL DEATH PENALTY STATUTE IS 
CONSTITUTIONAL  
 A.  The Death Penalty Does Not Constitute A Cruel And Unusual 
Punishment  
 McVeigh's claim that the death penalty violates the Eighth 
Amendment's prohibition against cruel and unusual punishment 
(DE 454, pp. 47-49)  is foreclosed by Supreme Court precedent. 
See McCleskey v. Kemp, 481 U.S. 279, 296-297, 300-302 (1987); 
Gregg v. Georgia, 428 U.S. 153, 169, 187 (1976)  (lead opinion); 
id. at 207, 226 (White, J., concurring).   
 
B.  Section 3595 Provides For Meaningful Appellate Review  Of 
All Federal Death Sentences   
McVeigh contends that the federal capital sentencing statute 
contained in 18 U.S.C. 3591, et seq., is constitutionally invalid 
because it fails to provide for meaningful appellate review of death 
sentences imposed under its provisions.  DE 454, pp. 17-21. 
Although the Supreme Court has often alluded to the importance of 
meaningful appellate review in upholding the validity of various 
state capital sentencing schemes (See, e.q., Parker v. Dugger, 498 
U.S. 308, 321 (1991); Clemons v. Mississippi, 494 U.S. 738, 749 
(1990)  (collecting cases)),  the Court has never specified the 
components of such review and in no instance has it invalidated a 
capital  sentencing  scheme  for  failing  to  accord  meaningful 
appellate review.  See Gregg, 428 U.S. at 195; Proffitt v. Florida, 
428 U.S. 242, 258 (1976).  However structured, appellate review 
procedures are "meaningful" if they are sufficient to "promote[] 
reliability  and  consistency"  (Clemons,  494  U.S.  at  749)  and 
"ensur[e]  that the death penalty is not imposed arbitrarily or 
irrationally" (Parker, 498 U.S. at 321).  As we show" the instant  
appellate review provisions, which track in substantial part the  
U.S. at 166-168, review provisions found adequate in Gregg, 198, 
ensure meaningful appellate review.l   
 
Contrary to McVeigh (DE 454, p. 19), Section 3595(a) does not 
jeopardize meaningful appellate review by providing for review of 
death sentences only "upon appeal by the defendant" See United 
States v. Davis,  F. Supp., 1995 automatically. WL 628013, at *7 
(E.D. La. Oct. 23, 1995)  ("automatic appellate review . . . has not 
been held to be constitutionally required"). McVeigh  speculates  
that  imposing  on  a  capital  defendant  the obligation of filing a 
notice of appeal "takes fatal advantage of a condemned person at 
the height of his vulnerability," but the simple act of filing a notice 
is far from burdensome given the multiple  counsel  with  which  
federal  capital  defendants  are routinely provided at all levels of 
the proceedings (see 18 U.S.C. 3005; 21 U.S.C. 848(q)(4)-(8)) and 
the requirement that the court clerk file the notice if the defendant 
so requests.  Fed. R. Crim. P. 32(c)(5).  In the rare case where a 
condemned prisoner wishes to do  so,  the  Constitution  is  not  
offended  by  a  knowing and intelligent waiver of the right to seek 
review of a death sentence.  See, e.g.,  Gilm v. Utah, 429 U.S. 1012 
. 
 
Nor does  Section  3595  "sharply  curtail[]"  the  scope  of 
appellate review in capital cases.  DE 454, pp. 17, 20-21.  Section 
3595(a) expressly  contemplates  the  parallel  pursuit  of  a 
conventional appeal from the underlying judgment of conviction. 
Section 3595(b), in turn, makes clear that appellate courts "shall 
review the entire record of the capital trial and sentencing 
proceeding. Finally,  Section 3595(c)  mandates that appellate 
courts shall address all substantive and procedural issues raised on 
the appeal of a sentence of death, n and requires that a death 
sentence be vacated if the court determines that the sentence "was 
imposed under the influence of . . . any . . . arbitrary factor" or that 
the evidence failed to "support the special finding of the existence 
of the required [statutory] aggravating factor."  It is thus clear 
"[t]he federal procedure of review of a sentence of death is 
exhaustive" under Section 3595.  Davis, supra, at *7.  As is true of 
the largely similar appellate review provisions in 21 U.S.C.  
848(q), nothing in the statute "alter[s]  .  .  . ordinary standards of 
review"; to the contrary, the special provisions of section 3595 
"serve to emphasize the serious nature of capital cases and the 
importance of careful review." United States v. Chandler, 996 F.2d 
1073, 1083 (llth Cir. 1993), cert. denied, 114 S. Ct. 2724 (1994).    
 
Section 3595(c)(2)(C) also provides that an appellate court n shall 
remand" if it finds that the capital proceedings "involved any other 
legal error requiring reversal of the sentence that was properly  
preserved  for  appeal  under  the  rules  of  criminal procedure."  
The provision does not alter the meaningfulness of the review. In 
the first place,  the provision is limited in application to "other 
legal errors]" than those pertaining to the evidentiary sufficiency of 
the special findings or the existence of "arbitrary factors" 
influencing the imposition of a death sentence. Federal courts have 
consistently construed similar language in 21 U.S.C. 848(q)(3) 
pertaining to the latter two categories of errors as sufficiently broad 
to "require review of any error of law occurring during the 
sentencing phase of the trial."  United States v. Pretlow, 779 
F.Supp. 758, 761-764, 769 (D.N.J. 1991).  See also United States 
v. Walker, F. Supp. , 1995 WL 603587, at *5-6 (N.D.N.Y. Sept. 
26, 1995); United States v. Bradley  880 F. Supp. 271, 282-283 
(M.D. Pa. 1994); United States v. Pitera, 795 F.Supp. 546,  566-
567  (E.D.N.Y.),  aff'd,  986  F.2d 499  (2d Cir.  1992) (table).  Just 
as "no aspect of a capital sentencing hearing is impervious to 
appellate review" under Section 848(q)(3), there is "'no basis for 
thinking that [a] court of appeals will be limited in its power fully 
to review any sentence imposed" under Section 3595. Pitera, 795 
F. Supp. at 567.  Moreover, as Fed. R. Crim. P. 52(b) preserves  for  
appeal  n [p] lain  errors  or  defects  affecting substantial rights" 
that "were not brought to the attention of the [district] court," there 
is no reason to think that plain errors during  a  capital  sentencing  
hearing  that  affect  a  capital defendant's  substantial  rights  
would not  be  reviewable under Section 3595(c)(2)(C) as having 
been "preserved for appeal under the rule[]  of criminal procedure" 
governing plain error. Cf.  
 
Chandler,  996  F.2d at  1086,  1097,  1099 n.  7  (comprehensively 
reviewing a broad range of  substantive  and  procedural  issues 
relating to death sentence, including plain error review of claims 
not raised in the district court); United States v. Flores, 63 F.3d 
1342 (5th Cir. 1995)  (comprehensive review accorded).  Section 
3595  thus does not  diminish any other appellate rights, but 
instead provides additional procedural rights of review of death 
sentences.  Accordingly, there is no merit to defendant McVeigh's 
claim that Section 3595 violates equal protection by "singl[ing]  
out  condemned  federal  prisoners  for  diminished appellate 
review" (DE 454, p. 21).  See Bradley, 880 F. Supp. at 283 
(rejecting similar claim).   
 
C. The Federal Death Penalty Statute's Relaxed Evidentiary 
Standards Are Not Unconstitutional   
Section  3593(c)  provides  that  information  at  capital sentencing 
hearings "is admissible regardless of its admissibility under the 
rules governing admission of evidence at criminal trials except that 
information may be excluded if its probative value is outweighed 
by the danger of creating unfair prejudice, confusing the issues, or 
misleading the jury."  Contrary to McVeigh's claim (DE 454, pp. 
21-23), this provision is constitutional.   
 
The Supreme Court has held that relaxed evidentiary standards are 
appropriate at capital sentencing hearings. See Gregg, 428 U.S. at 
203-204; Williams v. New York, 337 U.S. 241 (1949).  See also,  
Schlup v.  Delo,  115 S. Ct.  851,  867 n. 44  (1995)  ("our permit  
reduced  procedural  protections  at decisions sentencing").  In 
Gregg, in rejecting a similar attack on Georgia's statute,  the  Court  
expressly stated that  the  legislature had unwisely . . . chosen not 
to impose unnecessary restrictions on the evidence that could be 
offered" since it was "desirable for the jury to have as much 
information as possible when it makes the sentencing decision." 
428 U.S.  at 203-204. Thus,  the Court concluded that "it is 
preferable not to impose restrictions," as long as the evidence 
presented at a capital sentencing hearing did not unfairly prejudice 
the accused. Ibid. In enacting Section 3593(c), Congress made the 
same permissible decision.  Cf. Bradley, 880 F. Supp. at 290.   
 
Every court that has considered the validity of a similarly- worded  
evidentiary  provision  in  the  Title  21  death  penalty procedures, 
21 U.S.C. 848(j), has concluded that its language is 
constitutionally "sufficient . . . to ensure the reliability of the 
information offered at sentencing. n Walker, supra, at *14.  See 
Bradley, 880 F. Supp. at 290-291; Pitera, 795 F. Supp. at 564-566; 
Pretlow, 779 F. Supp. at 769-771.  There is no reason for this court  
to  reach  a  different  conclusion  with  respect  to  the See Davis, 
supra, at *5 evidentiary standard in Section 3593) (language in 
Section 3593(c) requires "heightened as opposed to lessened 
reliability").  
 
II.  THE ATTORNEY GENERAL ACTED WITHIN THE SCOPE 
OF HER 
 PROSECUTORIAL DISCRETION IN DETERMINING THAT 
THE 
 DEATH PENALTY SHOULD BE SOUGHT 
A.  Defendant McVeigh Was Not Arbitrarily Singled Out For 
Capital Prosecution 
 
There is no basis for McVeigh's claim that he was arbitrarily and 
irrationally singled out for capital prosecution because of  
"political opportunism" on the part of the Attorney General (DE 
454, pp. 14-17).  Given that McVeigh is charged with the deadliest 
act of domestic terrorism in our Nation's history, it was hardly 
arbitrary to seek the death penalty.  Cf. Pitera, 795 F. Supp. at 567-
568 (rejecting claim that the "purported head of a significant drug 
enterprise, n who was "personally alleged to have committed seven 
murders," was arbitrarily selected for capital prosecution). 
 
As the Supreme Court has made clear, the Eighth Amendment is 
not violated because prosecutors possess unfettered discretion to 
determine  which  death-eligible  defendants  will  be  capitally 
prosecuted and which will not be.  See McCleskey, 481 U.S. at 
296- 297, 306-308, 313; Gregg, 428 U.S. at 199 (lead opinion); id. 
at See also, Silagy v. Peters, 905 F.2d 225 (White, J., concurring) 
986, 993-994 (7th Cir. 1990), cert. denied, 498 U.S. 1110 (1991); 
Pitera, 795 F. Supp. at 568.  Absent a showing that the decision to 
seek the death penalty was based on invidious considerations 
something McVeigh does not even allege to have occurred here 
"the policy considerations behind a prosecutor's traditional 'wide 
discretion' suggest the impropriety of our requiring prosecutors to 
defend their decisions to seek death penalties."  McCleskey, 481 
U.S. at 296 (footnote omitted).2  
 
Nor do remarks of the President and the Attorney General in the 
immediate aftermath of the bombing furnish  basis for judicial 
second-guessing of the death penalty decision. Prosecutors "need 
not be entirely 'neutral and detached'" (Marshall v. Jerrico, 446 
U.S. 238, 248 (1980)) or "disinterested" (Wright v. United States, 
732 F.2d 1048, 1056 (2d Cir. 1984), cert. denied, 469 U.S. 1106 
(1985)) in their enforcement of the law.  As the Nation's chief law 
enforcement officers, the assurances given by the President and the 
Attorney General that those responsible for the bombing would be 
identified,  apprehended,  and vigorously prosecuted to the full 
extent of the law represent a permissible "general zealousness in 
the enforcement process. n See Jerrico, 446 U.S. at 250.  
 
B.  Internal Departmental Procedures Followed By The Attorney 
General In Deciding Whether To Seek The Death Penalty  Not 
Confer Any Rights On Capital Defendants 
 
Under Section 9-10.000 of the United States Attorneys' Manual, 
which  "sets  forth  policy  and  procedures"  applicable  to  all 
potential  federal  capital  cases,  the  Attorney  General  must 
personally authorize prosecutors to seek the death penalty.  Once 
her authorization has been received, federal prosecutors may file 
notice under 18 U.S.C. 3593(a) of their intent to seek the death 
penalty upon conviction.  Nichols asserts that Section 3593(a)'s 
notice provisions "are carried into force by the regulations issued 
by the Attorney General" and thus that the Attorney General's 
decision to authorize seeking the death penalty "is not an exercise 
of prosecutorial discretion," but instead a "formal decision" that 
must be accompanied by an array of procedural rights, including 
the  
right to discovery of all internal Department of Justice memoranda 
upon which the Attorney General based her decision and judicial 
review of the decision itself.  DE 455, pp. 31-32.   
 
We have fully answered these same claims in our response to 
McVeigh's motion to disqualify the Attorney General and to 
preclude the government  from seeking the death penalty. DE 240. 
As explained there, the internal Justice Department procedures are 
neither required by law nor enforceable by criminal defendants 
against  the  government. Rather,  the  capital  authorization 
procedures are merely internal guidelines that assist United States 
Attorneys in recommending, intermediary Departmental officials 
in reviewing, and the Attorney General in determining whether 
capital prosecutions should be initiated.  Such charging decisions 
are at the heart of prosecutorial discretion, and are immune from 
judicial scrutiny in the absence of a preliminary showing that the 
charging decision was made for invidious reasons.  See supra, p. 8; 
Heckler v.  Chaney,  470  U.S.  821,  831-832  (1985). Nor are  
internal Department of Justice memoranda that pertain to the 
exercise of prosecutorial discretion subject to discovery in the 
absence of a prima facie showing of selective prosecution.  See 
Walker, supra, at *21-22.  Nichols has made no such showing.  
 
III.  THERE IS NO CONSTITUTIONAL REQUIREMENT 
THAT THE GRAND 
  JURY ALLEGE THE AGGRAVATING FACTORS UPON 
WHICH THE 
  GOVERNMENT WILL RELY AT A CAPITAL SENTENCING 
HEARING 
  
Nichols (DE 45S, pp. 12-19) contends that the statutory notice 
provision  in  Section  3593(a)  violates  the  Fifth  Amendment  
Indictment Clause by permitting prosecutors, rather than the grand 
jury, to determine whether the death penalty should be sought and 
what aggravating factors justify its imposition.  Unsurprisingly, 
Nichols cites no case holding that such peculiarly prosecutorial 
determinations as the decisions whether and upon what terms to 
seek the death penalty are constitutionally committed to the grand 
jury. Cf. Spinkellink v. Wainwright, 578 F.2d 582, 609 (5th Cir. 
1978) (n [Defendant] cites no case, federal or state, which requires 
the prosecutor to list in the indictment the aggravating 
circumstances on which he will rely in seeking the death penaltyn), 
cert. denied, 440 U.S.  976  (1979) .3 Section 3593(a)'s allocation 
of these discretionary  decisions to the  prosecutor  comports  with 
constitutional principles. See McCleskey, 481 U.S. at 296-297, 
306-308; Gregg, 428 U.S. at 199.  
 
The Fifth Amendment requirement that "[n]o person shall be held 
to answer for a capital, or otherwise infamous crime, unless on . . . 
indictment of a Grand Jury" is satisfied by an indictment that 
"contains the elements of the offense charged" as "set forth in the 
words of the statute itself." Hamling v. United States, 418 U.S. 87, 
117 (1974).  For Fifth Amendment purposes, the "legislature's 
definition of the elements of the offense is usually dispositive."  
McMillan v. Pennsylvania, 477 U.S. 79, 85 (1986) . Thus, when 
not expressly incorporated into the statutory definition of an 
offense,  the Supreme Court has refused to treat as an "element of 
the crime[]" "sentencing factor[s] that come[] into play only after 
the defendant has been found guilty" of the charged criminal 
offense.  Id. at 85-86. In such circumstances, "there is no Fifth 
Amendment right to grand jury indictment on the sentencing 
facts." Buckley v. Butler,  825 F.2d 895, 903 (5th Cir. 1987), cert. 
denied, 486 U.S. 1009 (1988).   
 
These principles apply in capital cases, in which the Supreme 
Court  has  repeatedly made clear that  aggravating factors are 
offenses" (Walton v. Arizona, 497 U.S. neither "separate . 639, 648 
(1990), quoting Poland v. Arizona,  476 U.S. 147, 156 (1986) ) nor 
"'elements' of any offense. n Lewis v. Jeffers, 497 U.S. 764, 782 
(1990) . Accord Hildwin v. Florida, 490 U.S. 638, 640-641 (1989); 
Cabana v. Bullock, 474 U.S. 376, 385 (1986). "Like the  
[enhancement  factor]  in  McMillan,  the  existence  of  an 
aggravating factor . . . instead is 'a sentencing factor that comes 
into  play only  after  the  defendant  has  been  found  guilty."  
Hildwin,  490 U.S.  at 640. See also,  Walton,  497 U.S.  at 648 
(aggravating  factors  serve  only  as  "standards  to  guide  [the 
sentencer]").  Indeed, because aggravating factors are not offense 
elements necessary for conviction -- and, hence, are not within the 
purview of the Fifth Amendment's Indictment Clause -- the 
Supreme Court has recognized that n [t]he Constitution permits the 
trial judge,  acting alone,  to impose a capital sentence." Harris v. 
Alabama, 115 S. Ct. 1031 (1995).   
 
Under the  federal capital  sentencing scheme,  aggravating factors 
play a similar post-conviction role in guiding the jury's exercise of 
its capital sentencing discretion. The statutory aggravating factors 
identified in Section 3592(c) are contained in a separate chapter of 
the criminal code than the capital offenses charged in the 
indictment and in no way add to the elements necessary  for  
conviction under  any of  the  charged offenses. Accordingly, there 
was no requirement under the Fifth Amendment's Indictment 
Clause that the aggravating factors be alleged by the grand jury.  
Cf. People v. Owens, 464 N.E.2d 261, 269 (Ill.) ("the indictment 
was  constitutionally sufficient  because  it  charged defendant with 
the offense of murder; "there was no constitutional requirement 
that any aggravating factor be charged), cert. denied, 469 U.S. 963 
(1984).   
 
Nor is a different conclusion required because the mental 
culpability "element" required by 18 U.S.C. 3591(a)(2) for Eighth 
Amendment proportionality purposes (see Tison v. Arizona, 481 
U.S. 137, 157-158 (1987); Enmund v. Florida, 458 U.S. 782, 797 
(1982)) is alleged only in the death penalty notices and will be 
proved at the capital penalty hearing.  Merely because the jury at 
the time of sentencing must make a "gateway" finding as to the 
existence of a mental culpability factor under Section 3S91(a) does 
not mean that such factors are offense "elements" that must be 
included in an indictment.  The Supreme Court has explained that 
its "ruling in Enmund does not concern the guilt or innocence of 
the defendant -- it establishes no new elements of the crime of 
murder that must be found by the jury" and it 'does not affect the 
state's definition of any substantive offense, even a capital offense.' 
n Cabana, 474 U.S.  at 385  & n.  3. Because the proportionality 
inquiry is distinct from the jury's determination whether the 
elements of a capital offense are established,  the  Court noted that 
Enmund neither n imposed any particular form of procedure" that 
the States must  follow nor identified the  "precise point in  [a 
State's] criminal process" at which an Enmund finding must be 
made. 474 U.S. at 386 (emphasis in original). Indeed, it was 
regarded as constitutionally irrelevant whether the Enmund finding 
was made at trial or on appeal.  Ibid.  Clearly then, the culpability 
factor need not be alleged in an indictment charging a capital 
offense.   
 
IV. THE DEATH PENALTY NOTICES WERE SUFFICIENT TO 
INFORM DEFENDANTS OF THE FACTORS ON WHICH THE 
GOVERNMENT INTENDS TO RELY AT ANY CAPITAL 
SENTENCING HEARING 
 
Relying  on  Fed.  R.  Crim.  P.  7(c)'s  requirement  that 
indictments and information must contain "a plain, concise, and 
definite written statement of the essential facts constituting the 
offense charged," Nichols argues (DE 455, pp. 19-21) that the  14  
death penalty notice was facially insufficient to apprise him of the 
aggravating factors on which the government ,intended to rely at 
any capital sentencing hearing.  As we have shown above, 
however, aggravating  factors  are  neither  "offenses"  nor  
"elements"  of offenses that need be alleged by indictment.  As 
such, the pleading requirements in Rule 7(c) do not apply to death 
penalty notices. 
 
Section 3593(a)'s notice provision is not elaborate: in addition  to  
informing  the  defendant  and  the  court  that  the government 
intends to seek the death penalty in the event of a conviction,  the 
government's notice need only "set[]  forth the aggravating factor 
or factors that the government . . . proposes to prove as justifying a 
sentence of death. n  In Chandler, 996 F.2d at 1089,  the court 
described a comparable notice provision in 21 U.S.C. 848(h) as 
merely requiring that the government provide the defendant with "a 
list" identifying each aggravating factor on which it intends to rely.  
Likewise, in United States v. Cooper, 754 F. Supp. 617, 621 & n. 
7, 635-637 (N.D. Ill. 1990), the court upheld the sufficiency of 
death penalty notices that identified the aggravating factors with 
the same degree of specificity as the instant notices.  See also, 
Bradley, 880 F. Supp. at 283-284, 286- 287; Owens, 464 N.E.2d at 
270 (reference to subsection of statutory aggravating factors relied 
upon provided sufficient notice).   
 
Apart from Section 3593(a)'s listing requirement, there is no 
constitutional requirement that the government provide a detailed 
description before trial of the aggravating factors upon which it 
will rely at a capital sentencing hearing.  Courts have often held 
that the enumeration of aggravating factors in a state's capital 
sentencing statute itself accords a capital defendant sufficient 
notice as to the factors on which the prosecution might be expected 
to rely in seeking the death penalty, without further need of a case-
specific listing of aggravating factors.  See Clark v. Dugger, 834 
F.2d 1561,  1566  (llth Cir.  1987)  (collecting cases), cert. denied, 
485 U.S. 982 (1988); Spinkellink, 578 F.2d at 609-610. There is 
similarly no requirement that the prosecution provide capital 
defendants in advance with a road map of the theory of its case in 
aggravation or the evidence that it will present to prove the 
existence of the aggravating factors on which it will rely. See 
Cooper,  754 F. Supp. at 621; Williams v. Commonwealth, 450 
S.E.2d 365, 372 (Va. 1994).  The instant notices identify the five 
statutory  aggravating  factors  by  reference  to  the  statutory 
citation and in language that tracked the statute and identify four 
other  non-statutory aggravating  factors  (including the  factor 
pertaining to victim impact, that tracked statutory language) with 
comparable specificity.  A fortiori, they are legally sufficient.  
 
Finally, defendants' notice complaints ring hollow when the 
alleged aggravating factors are viewed in conjunction with the 
indictment allegation" referenced in the death penalty notices. Each 
and every aggravating factor set forth in the instant death penalty 
notices is grounded in facts alleged in the indictment and in the 
horrible consequences that inevitably followed.   
 
V.  THE FIVE STATUTORY AGGRAVATING FACTORS 
ALLEGED IN THE  DEATH PENALTY NOTICES ARE 
LEGALLY VALID IN ALL RESPECTS   
A.  The Section 3592(c)(1) Aggravating Factor That The  Victims' 
Deaths Occurred During The Defendants' Commission Of Various 
Enumerated Felony Offenses Both Narrows The Class of Death-
Eligible Defendants And Is Otherwise Constitutional  
1.  The Section 3592(c)(1) Aggravating Factor Is Not 
Unconstitutional Because It Duplicates Offenses Or Elements Of 
Offenses Charged In The Indictment   
 
Under 18 U.S.C. 3592(c)(1), it is an aggravating factor if "death or 
injury resulting in death"  has occurred during the commission of 
20 enumerated offenses.  The death penalty notices here cite the 
Section 3592(c)(1) aggravating factor and allege that "'deaths  or  
injuries  resulting  in  deaths"  occurred  during defendants'  
commission  of  five  of  the  enumerated  offenses. Defendants 
contend (DE 454, pp. 23-26; DE 455, pp.  25-29)  that reliance on 
the Section 3952(c)(1)  factor is constitutionally impermissible, as 
the offenses enumerated in Section 3592(c)(1) duplicate in whole 
or in part elements of the offenses charged in the indictment.  In 
defendants' view, this duplication of offenses (or offense elements)  
as aggravating factors  is  impermissible because it fails to narrow 
the class of persons eligible for the death penalty and skews the 
weighing process in favor of death.  
 
Defendants'  argument  is wholly answered by Lowenfield v. 
Phelps, 484 U.S. 231 (1988).  As the Court there stated, "[t]he use 
of 'aggravating circumstances' is not an end in itself, but a means 
of genuinely narrowing the class of death-eligible persons and 
thereby channeling the jury's discretion. R Id. at 244.  n [T]his 
narrowing function may .  .  . be performed by jury findings at 
either the sentencing phase of the trial or the guilt phase. n Id. at 
244-245.  Accordingly, the fact that an aggravating circumstance 
found at the sentencing phase duplicates in whole or in part the 
elements of the crime found at the guilt phase "does not make [a 
death] sentence constitutionally infirm. n Id. at 246.   
 
Cases decided under the federal capital sentencing statute 
applicable to certain drug-related murders, 21 U.S.C. 848(e), et 
seq. (a "weighing" statute), uniformly hold that Lowenfield permits 
juries to consider as a statutory aggravating factor a mental 
culpability element (that the offender intentionally killed) that 
duplicates an element of the capital murder offense.  See Flores, 63 
F.3d at 1370-1372 & n. 31; Chandler, 996 F.2d at 1093; Walker, 
supra,  at *7; Bradley,  880 F. Supp. at 287-289; Pitera, 795 F. 
Supp. at 556-557; Pretlow, 779 F. Supp. at 771-773; Cooper, 754 
F. Supp. at 621-622.  As the Fifth Circuit explained in Flores, not 
all murderers necessarily intend to kill; accordingly, because the 
intent factor applied to only a subclass of all murderers,  its 
consideration "genuinely narrow[ed] the class of persons eligible 
for the death penalty and reasonably justif[ied]  the imposition of a 
more severe sentence on [a particular] defendant compared to 
others found guilty of murder."  63 F.3d at 1370-1371, quoting,  
Zant v. Stephens, 462 U.S. 862, 877 (1983).   
 
The fact that a capital homicide has occurred during the 
commission of a felony is a valid aggravating factor.  See Blystone 
v. Pennsylvania, 494 U.S. 299, 306-307 (1990).  In the context of 
felony-murder prosecutions after Lowenfield,  "federal courts of 
appeals have consistently held that a sentencing jury can consider 
an element of the capital offense as an aggravating circumstance 
even if it i8 duplicitous. n Deputy v. Taylor, 19 F.3d 1485, 1502 
(3d Cir.) (collecting cases), cert. denied, 114 S. Ct. 2730 (1994). 
Indeed, the Eighth Circuit, which once adopted a rule that barred 
the duplication of offense elements as aggravating factors, has 
since abandoned that position as incompatible with Lowenfield.  
See Snell v.  Lockhart,  14  F.3d 1289,  1304-1305  (8th Cir.),  cert. 
denied, 115 S. Ct. 419 (1994); Perry v. Lockhart, 871 F.2d 1384, 
1392-1393 (8th Cir.), cert. denied, 493 U.S. 959 (1989).5 
 
That defendants caused the deaths of more than 160 persons during 
their commission of various explosives-related offenses 
enumerated in Section 3592(c)(1)  is  a  factor that  "genuinely 
narrows" the class of death-eligible defendants within the meaning 
of Lowenfield and Zant. Not all murderers subject to federal 
prosecution engage in the commission of the serious felony 
offenses enumerated in Section 3592(c)(1).  Because the Section 
3592(c)(1) aggravator thus  "appl[ies]  only to a  subclass of 
defendants" convicted of  a homicide offense and not  to  "every 
defendant eligible for the death penalty" (Tuilaepa v. California, 
114 S. Ct. 2630, 2635 (1994), quoting, Arave v. Creech, 113 S. Ct. 
1534, 1542 (1993)), it is constitutionally sound.  Cf. Flores, supra. 
6   
 
Nor is a different conclusion required by Strinqer v. Black, 503 
U.S. 222 (1992).  There, the Court held that jury consideration of 
an unconstitutionally vague aggravating factor (that the offense 
was "heinous, atrocious or cruel") was particularly problematic 
under a "'weighing" statute because "it created the risk that the jury 
will treat the defendant as more deserving of the death penalty than 
he otherwise might be by relying upon the existence of an illusory 
circumstance."  503 U.S. at 235.  Unlike in Stringer,  it  cannot  
plausibly  be  argued  that  the  Section  3592(c)(1) aggravating  
factor  here  that  duplicates  offense  elements  i9 
unconstitutionally vague.  As such, Strinqer is irrelevant to the 
resolution of the duplication issue.  See Johnson v. Singletary, 991 
F.2d 663,  669  (llth Cir.),  cert.  denied,  113 S.  Ct.  2049 (1993);  
Bradley  880  F.  Supp.  at  289  (emphasis  in original) ("Strinqer 
addressed the use of invalid factors in the weighing process, not 
the use of duplicative factors.  Since the duplicative factor  is not 
constitutionally invalid,  and is  a permissible statutory aggravating 
factor, it may be considered by the jury in arriving at a sentencing 
decision."); Pitera, 795 F.Supp. at 557. Lowenfeld's holding  that  a  
duplicating aggravating  factor  i8 constitutionally permissible does 
not turn on the nature of the jurisdiction or the stage at which the 
narrowing occurs.   
 
2.  The Section 3592(c)(1) Aggravating Factor Is Not  Improper 
Because It Alleges That Defendants' Death-Resulting Conduct 
Occurred During Their Commission Of Multiple Enumerated 
Predicate Offenses   
Relying on Cook v. State, 369 So.2d 1251, 1256 (Ala. 1978), and 
similar state cases, McVeigh contends (DE 454, pp. 26-29) that the 
death penalty notices are defective because, in alleging the 
existence  of  the  aggravating  factor  in  Section  3592(c)(1) 
pertaining to "death during the commission of another crime," they 
allege the requisite "death(s) or injur[ies] resulting in death'" 
occurred during the commission of five explosives-related offenses 
enumerated in Section 3592(c)(1).  In Cook and other state cases 
relied upon, the courts held that state capital sentencing schemes 
that counted as aggravating circumstances both (1) the fact that  the  
murder  was  committed  during  the  commission  of  an 
underlying felon offense that was robbery, a (2) the fact that the 
murder was committed for pecuniary gain,  were  improperly 
weighted towards death.  McVeigh's effort to invoke this rationale 
in attacking the formulation of the Section 3592(c)(1) aggravating 
factor in the death penalty notices fails for two reasons.   
 
First, the rule that McVeigh urges is not mandated by the Supreme 
Court's Eighth Amendment jurisprudence; rather,  as was noted in 
Wiley v. Puckett, 969 F.2d 86, 95-97 (5th Cir. 1992), the reasoning 
in cases like Cook derived entirely from state-based rules.  Second, 
the Section 3592(c)(1) factor in this case does not rely on a double-
counting of a single offense element to establish multiple 
aggravating factors.  The opposite is true:  the instant Section 
3592(c)(1) aggravating factor relies on multiple means to establish 
the existence of the single factor that the "death(s) or injur(ies) 
resulting in death" occurred during the commission of an 
enumerated offense. Cf. Griffin v. United States,  502 U.S. 
46(1991)  In Flores, 63 F.3d at 1370, 1372-1373, the court held 
that it was permissible for the government to rely on multiple 
subparts of  the  mental  culpability factor,  which is classified as  
an aggravating factor and weighed under  21 U.S.C.  848(n)(1),  to 
establish the existence of that factor.  The same reasoning applies 
here. By committing their death-producing bombing attack in a 
manner that violated several of the offense provisions enumerated 
in  Section  3592(c)(1),  defendants  effectively  dictated  the 
formulation of the Section 3592(c)(1) aggravating factor.  Having 
done so, neither the statute nor the Constitution precludes the 
government from relying on those multiple means to prove the 
existence of the aggravating factor.   
 
McVeigh claims that, by relying on multiple offenses to prove the 
Section 3592(c)(1) aggravating factor, it is likely that a jury will 
consider each predicate offense as a separate aggravating factor 
and thereby increase the likelihood that it will impose a death 
sentence when it weighs any mitigating factors against the 
aggravating factors.  McVeigh's concern, which wrongly 
presupposes that  the  sentencing process  involves  "a rigid and 
mechanical parsing of statutory aggravating factors" (Barclay v. 
Florida, 463 U.S. 939, 950 (1983) (plurality opinion), can be 
alleviated by jury instructions that  eschew quantitative  counting 
in favor of  a qualitative evaluation of the factors and the evidence 
supporting them and that further apprise the jury that the alleged 
multiple offenses are not factors themselves, but simply multiple 
means by which  the  existence of  the  Section  3592(c)(1)  factor 
may be established.  Cf.  Chandler, 996 F.2d at 1093 (noting 
ameliorative effect of instructions explaining weighing process); 
Pitera, 795 F. Supp.  at  557  (same). Similarly,  assuming that 
there  is any requirement that the jurors agree as to the means by 
which an aggravating factor is established, McVeigh is free to 
propose a jury unanimity instruction informing the jurors that they 
must agree as to the existence of any of the alleged predicate 
offenses.  
 
3.  Congress Intended To Include Death-Resulting Violations of 
The Weapons of Mass Destruction Statute As An Aggravating 
Factor Under Section 3S92(c)(1)  
The death penalty notices allege, as part of the aggravating factor  
specified  in  Section  3592(c)(1),  that  "the  deaths  or  injuries 
resulting in death occurred," inte  alia,  "during the commission of 
an offense under  .  .  .  18 U.S.C.  2332a  (use of weapons of mass 
destruction)."  Noting that the text of Section 3592(c)(1)  refers  to  
"section  2339  (use  of  weapons  of  mass destruction," defendant 
Nichols contends (DE 455, pp. 22-23) that the aggravating factor 
as alleged in our notices is impermissibly vague because it is based 
on a "plain invention of terms that do not appear in the statute," 
thereby alleging an aggravating factor "that Congress did not at all 
provide." 
 
Congress undoubtedly made a technical error when it referred to 
"section 2339 as the citation for the statute criminalizing the (use 
of weapons of mass destruction).":  there is no "section 2339" in 
Title 18, and the only provision in Title 18 entitled, "use of 
weapons of mass destruction, n is codified as 18 U.S.C.  2332a. 
"Under general principles of statutory construction," however, it 
has been recognized that "where .  .  .  the legislature has made a 
mistake in a reference in a statute to another statute and the real 
intent of  the legislature  is manifest  and would be defeated by 
adherence to the terms of  the mistaken 
 reference, a court may disregard the mistaken reference or read it 
as corrected in order to give effect to the legislative intent.  Curry 
v. Department of Corrections, 423 So.2d 584, 585 (Fla. Ct. App. 
1982). Colonial Life & Accident Ins. Co. v. American Family Life 
Assurance Co., 846 F. Supp. 454, 463 n. 14 (D.S.C. 1994).  See 
United States Independent Ins. Agents of America National Bank 
of Oregon v.  Inc., 113 S. Ct. 2173, 2182-2186 (1993).  By Section 
3592(c)(1)'s unambiguous reference to death-resulting violations of 
the "weapons of mass destruction" statute, it is evident that 
Congress intended to incorporate the offense described in Section 
2332a, rather than the non-existent provisions of "section 2339."'  
 
B.  The "Grave Risk Of Death" Aggravating Factor In  Section 
3592(c)(5) Is Not Unconstitutionally Vague   
Tracking the words of the statute, the death penalty notices allege 
that, in committing the capital offenses charged in the indictment, 
the defendants "created a grave risk of death to one or more 
persons in addition to the victim(s) of the offense(s). n 18 U.S.C. 
3592(c) (5).  Contrary to McVeigh's claim (DE 454, pp. 29- 30), 
the "grave risk of death" aggravating factor is not 
unconstitutionally vague. In Tuilaepa, 114 S.Ct. at 2635, the Court 
explained that [b]ecause the proper definition' of eligibility and 
selection factors often 'is not susceptible of   mathematical  
precision,'  .  .  . vagueness  review  is  quite deferential."  See also 
Walton,  497 U.S.  at  655. Hence,  an aggravating factor "is not 
unconstitutional if it has some 'common- sense core of meaning . . .  
that criminal juries should be capable of understanding.'" Tuilaepa,  
114 S.Ct. at 2635-2636, quoting, Jurek v. Texas, 428 U.S. 262, 279 
(1976)  (White, J. concurring).8   
 
In Brecheen v. Reynolds, 41 F.3d 1343, 1360-1361 (lOth Cir. 
1994), the Tenth Circuit applied this analysis in rejecting a claim 
that Oklahoma's "great risk of death to more than one person" 
aggravator was unconstitutionally vague.  See also Proffitt, 428 
U.S. at 256 (aggravating factor of "knowingly creat[ing] a great 
risk of death to many persons" was "not impermissibly vague").  
The same conclusion is warranted here. McVeigh has not shown 
that Section 3592(c)(5) is ambiguous; he has shown only that 
variously- worded state "risk of death" provisions have been 
accorded varying interpretations. See  Walker,  supra,  at  *10  
(rejecting  same collection of state cases as indicative of ambiguity 
in federal "grave risk of death" provision).  
 
By its plain terms, Section 3592(c)(5) is applicable whenever a 
defendant, during the commission of a capital offense, "knowingly 
creates] a grave risk of death to 1 or more persons in addition to the 
victim of the offense."  The rule of lenity cannot properly be 
invoked to give the Section 3592(c)(S)  aggravating factor its 
narrowest possible construction.  Cf. Moskal v. United States, 498 
U.S.  103,  107  (1990)  ("we  have  declined  to  deem  a  statute 
'ambiguous' for purposes of lenity merely because it was possible 
to articulate a [narrower] construction" or because there is "a 
division of judicial authority" as to its construction).  Defendant 
McVeigh has not shown why the grave risk of death created by his 
conduct -- exploding a massive truck bomb outside a crowded 
federal building -- would not fall within any reasonable 
construction of Section 3592(c)(5).  See Walker, supra, at *11.  See 
also, Gregg, 428 U.S. at 202-203 (lead opinion).  
 
C.  The "Substantial Planning And Premeditation" Aggravating 
Factor In Section 3592(c)(9) Is Not Vague   
Tracking the words of the statute, the death penalty notices allege 
that defendants "committed the offense(s) after substantial 
planning and premeditation to cause the death of one or more 
persons and to commit an act of terrorism."  18 U.S.C. 3592(c)t9). 
Defendants contend (DE 454, 30-33; DE 455, pp. 23) that the 
phrase "substantial planning and premeditation"  is 
unconstitutionally vague. However,  every court  that  has 
addressed a vagueness challenge  to  the  "substantial  planning  
and  premeditation" aggravating factor in 21 U.S.C. 848(n)(8) has 
concluded that it sufficiently channels the jury's deliberations to 
withstand such an attack.  See Flores, 63 F.3d at 1373-1374; 
Walker, supra, at *9; Cooper, 754 F. Supp. at 623-624.9  See also, 
Davis, supra, at *2 (rejecting vagueness challenge to Section 
3592(c)(9)).  The logic of these cases compels the same result here. 
 
As the court correctly recognized in Cooper, 754 F. Supp. at 623,  
"premeditation"  and  "planning"  are  "commonly understood" 
terms.  The "common-sense core of meaning" of these terms is not 
destroyed when "substantial" is coupled with "planning" in Section 
3592(c)(9).  "Substantiality," too, is a term that is frequently 
employed and commonly understood in the criminal law context.  
See Flores, 63 F.3d at 1373 (collecting examples); Cooper, 754 F. 
Supp. at 623. See also, Blystone,  494 U.S. at 308  ("substantia[l] 
impairment" as mitigating factor).  As the Supreme Court 
explained in addressing the adequacy of an instruction defining the 
concept of reasonable doubt in terms of "actual substantial doubt," 
"the word 'substantial' [is] commonly understood, [to] suggest a 
higher degree of doubt than is required for acquittal under the 
reasonable doubt  standard." Cage v.  Louisiana,  498  U.S.  39,  41  
(1990) (emphasis added).  Courts construing the "substantial 
planning and premeditation" aggravator have accorded the phrase 
"substantial planning" its "commonly understood" meaning (lbid.), 
connoting a higher quantum of planning than the minimum, 
sufficient for the commission of the acts of homicide or 
terrorism10 that must be its object. Thus,  the  "aggravator  is  
sufficiently  definite  and objective to pass constitutional muster."  
Flores, 63 F.3d at 1374.  
 
D.  The "Vulnerable Victim" Aggravating Factor In  Section 
3592(c)(11) Is Not Unconstitutionally Vague   
The death penalty notices allege as a statutory aggravating factor 
that "various victims were particularly vulnerable due to old age, 
youth, and infirmity."  18 U.S.C. 3592(c)(11).  Defendants contend 
(D. 454, pp. 33-34; DE 455, pp. 23-25) that the "vulnerable victim" 
aggravating factor is unconstitutionally vague, as it does not define 
"old age," "youth or "infirmity" and fails to impose a requirement 
that the defendants selected their victims based on these 
vulnerabilities.  An identical challenge to the validity of the 
"vulnerable victim" aggravating factor was rejected in Pretlow, 779 
F. Supp. at 774.  See also United States v. Boult, 905 F.2d 1137, 
1140 (8th Cir. 1990)  (similar terms in U.S.S.G. Guidelines 
Manual  3A1.1 "are not unconstitutionally vague").   
 
As defendants concede (DE 454, p. 33 n. 29; DE 455, p. 23), the 
Supreme Court has recognized that matters of "age" and "youth" 
are both relevant and sufficiently understandable to warrant their 
consideration in capital sentencing proceedings.  See Tuilaepa, 114 
S. Ct. at 2637-2638; Eddinqs v. Oklahoma, 4L U.S. 104, 115-116 
(1982).  That the Court has done so in the context of addressing the 
mitigating value that might be found in a defendant's "youth" and 
"age" does not cast doubt on their understandability merely 
because Congress has chosen to incorporate the terms into an 
aggravating factor.  See Pretlow, 779 F. Supp. at 774.  Each of the 
terms used in the Section 3592(c)(11)  aggravating factor has a 
"common-sense core of meaning" (Tuilaepa, 114 S. Ct. at 2636).  
See Webster's Third New International Dictionary (unabridged 
1981) at 1159 ("infirmity"); id. at 1570 ("old age"); id. at 2654 
("youth"). Moreover, the statute further refines the scope of these 
terms by requiring not only that victims be old, youthful, or infirm, 
but that they be "particularly vulnerable due to" such 
circumstances.  
 
Nor are these terms any less understandable because Section 
3592(c)(11) does not require that a capital defendant be aware of 
his victim's old age, youth, or infirmity.  Defendants must take 
their  crime  victims  as  they  find them. Thus,  there  is  no 
constitutional  requirement  that  a  defendant  be  aware  of  an 
aggravating circumstance pertaining to his victim in order for that 
circumstance to be considered at a capital sentencing hearing.  See 
Payne v. Tennessee, 501 U.S. 808, 837-839, 841 (1991)  (Souter, 
J., concurring); cf. United States v. Feola, 420 U.S. 671, 685 
(1975).   
 
At  bottom,  defendants'  challenge  is  not  so much one of 
vagueness, but that the government will be unable to prove that 
any homicide victims were "particularly vulnerable" because of 
"old age, youth, or infirmity."  Whether the government can 
succeed in establishing an actual basis for this aggrivating factor is 
an issue to be resolved at trial.  See Pretlow, 779 F. Supp. at 774.   
 
E.  The "High Public Officials" Aggravating Factor In  Section 
3592(c)(14) Is Not Unconstitutional 
The death penalty notices allege as a statutory aggravating factor 
that the defendants "committed the offense(s) against one or more 
federal public servants who were law enforcement officers, (a) 
while such victim(s) were engaged in the performance of official 
duties,  (b)  because of such victim(s)'  performance of official 
duties,  and  (c)  because  of  such victim(s)'  status  as  public 
servants."18 U.S.C.  3592(c)(14). Claiming that a recently-
promulgated regulation  (28 C.F.R. 64.2  (1995))  "dramatically 
expand[s] the categories of federal employees who qualify as "law 
enforcement officers," McVeigh argues (DE 454, pp. 34-35) that 
the "high public officials" aggravating factor is both 
unconstitutionally vague and "absurdly overbroad" because the 
new regulation has "stripped [Section 3592(c)(14)] of all its ability 
to meaningful narrow the class of offenders eligible for death." 
 
Contrary to McVeigh's claim, 28 C.F.R.  64.2 -- which was 
promulgated  by  the  Attorney  General  four  months  before  the 
enactment of the instant federal capital sentencing statute -- does 
not affect the scope of the "high public officials" aggravating factor 
or its "law enforcement officer" subset.11 Rather,  the regulation, 
which was lawfully promulgated under a delegation of authority  
contained  in  18  U.S.C.  1114 merely  expands  the designated 
categories of "federal officers and employees" who are protected 
under Section 1114's murder provisions.  Although Section 1114 
and the supplemental regulations undoubtedly cover federal 
officers who are "law enforcement officers," neither Section 1114 
nor the supplemental regulations were meant to be co-extensive 
with Section 3592(c)(14).  Hence, the fact that both Section 1114 
and the supplemental regulation include within their protections a 
wide variety  of  federal  "employees"  who  are  neither  "high 
public officials" nor "law enforcement officers" is wholly 
irrelevant in determining Section 3592(c)(14)'s constitutionality. 
 
Section  3592(c)(14)  expressly  defines  a  qualifying  "law 
enforcement officer" as "a public servant authorized by law . to 
engage in the prevention,  investigation, or prosecution,  or 
adjudication of an offense." In so doing, Section 3592(c)(14) 
genuinely narrows the class of death-eligible defendants in terms 
that jurors can readily understand and apply. See Roberts v. 
Louisiana, 431 U.S. 633,  636  (1977)  ("the fact that the murder 
victim was a peace officer performing his regular duties" is a 
permissible aggravating factor).12  
 
VI. THE GOVERNMENT MAY CONSTITUTIONALLY RELY 
ON THE NON STATUTORY AGGRAVATING FACTORS 
LISTED IN ITS DEATH PENALTY NOTICES  
A.  Congress Authorized The Government To Allege And The Jury 
To Consider Non-Statutory Aggravating Factors  
In addition to the 15 statutory  "aggravating factors for homicide"  
that  serve  to  narrow  the  class  of  death-eligible defendants, 18 
U.S.C. 3592(c) expressly provides that "[t]he jury . . .  may 
consider whether any other aggravating factors for which notice 
has been given exists."  Defendants nonetheless contend (DE 4s4, 
pp. 39-40; DE 455, pp. 29-30) that Congress did not authorize non-
statutory aggravating factors because Section 3591(a) provides that 
a defendant convicted of a capital offense "shall be sentenced to 
death" if the jury determines that a death sentence is justified "after 
consideration of the factors set forth in section 3592." Defendants 
read Section 3591(a) as thereby precluding reliance on any 
aggravating factor that  is not  statutorily delineated  in Section 
3592.  Defendants' claim is not well taken.   
 
It is a "cardinal rule" of construction "that a statute is to be read is 
to be read as a whole,  .  .  . since the meaning of statutory 
language, plain or not, depends on context."  King v. St. Vincent's 
Hospital, 502 U.S. 215, 221 (1991).  The permissibility of non-
statutory aggravating factors is a pervasive aspect of the instant 
capital sentencing scheme.  Thus, as a complement to the broad 
language in Section 3592(c) authorizing juries to consider non-
statutory aggravating factors, Section 35  (a) (2), in equally broad 
terms, empowers the government to notice any "aggravating factor 
or factors" that it will rely upon "as justifying a sentence of death[,]  
.  .  . including factors concerning the effect of the offense on the 
victim and the victim's family."  During the course of  a  capital  
sentencing  hearing,  the  government  is  further authorized to 
present information "as to any matter relevant to the aggravating 
factor permitted or sentence,  including any  . required  to be  
considered under  [S]ection  3592." 18 U.S.C. 3593(c).  At the 
conclusion of a capital penalty hearing, the jury is  obligated  to  
"return  special  findings  identifying  any aggravating factor or 
factors set forth in [S]ection 3592 found to exist and any other 
aggravating factor for which notice has been provided under 
[Section 3593 (a)]  found to exist. n In the event that  "an  
aggravating  factor  required  to  be  considered under [S]ection 
3592(c) is found to exist, n the jury is then obligated to "consider 
whether all the aggravating factor or factors found to exist"  
sufficiently outweigh any mitigating  factors  so as  to justify the 
imposition of a sentence of death. 
 
In view of this comprehensive capital sentencing scheme that 
unambiguously recognizes the role of non-statutory aggravating 
factors at every stage of the proceedings, Section 3591 (a) cannot 
carry the weight that defendants give it.  Read in the context of the 
statutory scheme, Section 3591 (a)'s reference to "the factors set 
forth in section 3592" does not bar consideration of non-statutory 
aggravating factors, but instead requires consideration of all factors 
authorized under Section 3592: statutory aggravating factors, non-
statutory aggravating factors, and mitigating factors, including 
mitigating factors asserted under 18 U.S.C. 3592(a) (8)'s "catch-
all" provision that is the functional counterpart to Section 3592(c)'s 
"catch-all" provision for non- statutory aggravating factors. Simply 
put, because capital sentencing statutes must permit unrestricted 
consideration of mitigating factors, Congress could not have 
intended Section 3591(a)'s language to be limited to statutory 
aggravating factors.   
 
The legislative history also shows Congress' clear intent to 
authorize reliance on non-statutory aggravating factors. 
Congressional proponents and opponents of the death penalty alike 
understood the provisions in the 1994 crime bill permitting 
consideration of "any other aggravating factor for which notice has 
been given" as authorizing the use of non-statutory aggravating 
factors. Hence, Rep. Watt, a death penalty opponent, sought to 
delete from the capital sentencing provisions of the crime bill all 
references to "other factors." See 140 Cong. Rec. H2339 (Apr. 14, 
1994) . Noting that the existing provisions in the crime bill (which 
later became law) permitted "the prosecuting attorney [to] specify 
whatever other aggravating factors he or she wishes to specify" in 
addition to those aggravating factors specifically listed in the 
statute, Rep. Watt stated that his proposed amendment would 
"limit the prosecutor to the aggravating factors which are specified  
in the  bill."  Ibid.  See  also, id.  at  H2339-H2340 (remarks of 
Rep. Hughes); id. at H2340 (remarks of Rep. Schumer).  
 
Rep. McCollum, a leading supporter of the death penalty, likewise 
understood that the Watt Amendment would remove from the 
crime bill "a catch-all" provision that enabled prosecutors "to 
frame and craft additional aggravating factors that might warrant 
the death penalty." Id. at H2340. Because Congress "co[uld] not 
think of . . . every possible contingency or for every possible type 
of case where the death penalty is warranted," Rep. McCollum 
stated that it was "constitutionally correct" to "leave the discretion 
in the hands of the prosecutors to look on each death penalty case 
on a case-by-case basis" and "craft an appropriate aggravating 
factor or two" in addition to those enumerated by statute. Id. at 
H2339. Without such a provision for non-statutory aggravating 
factors, Rep. McCollum cautioned that there was "the potential for 
grave injustice for [the] death penalty perhaps not being imposed 
in a case that has circumstances that are unusual or peculiar to it." 
Ibid. Rep. McCollum's view prevailed, and the watt Amendment to 
bar reliance on non-statutory aggravating factors was soundly 
defeated.  Id. at H2340-H2341.  The plain language of the statute 
and its legislative history defeat defendants' claim.  
 
B.  Congress Did Not Unconstitutionally Delegate Its Legislative 
Authority By Allowing Prosecutors To Rely on  Authority On 
Non-Statutory Aggravating Factors 
Equally unavailing is defendants' claim (DE 454, pp. 37-39; DE   
455 p. 31) that allowing non-statutory aggravating factors  
constitutes an unconstitutional delegation of legislative  [T] he 
[federal] sentencing function long has been a peculiarly shared 
responsibility among the Branches of Government and has never 
been thought of as the exclusive province of any one Branch."  
Mistretta v. United States, 488 U.S. 361, 390  (1989). Without 
doubt, Congress has the constitutional authority to define federal 
crimes and prescribe the quantum of punishment. Id. at 364.  
Congress exercised that authority when it enacted the various 
offenses contained in Sections 2332a, 844(f)), and 1114 and 
provided a range of penalties for their violation that includes the 
death penalty. Moreover,  as a judge-made rule,  in enacting capital 
penalty provisions, Congress is obligated to specify "statutory 
aggravating circumstances .  .  .  [that] circumscribe the class of 
persons eligible for the death penalty."  Zant, 462 U.S. at 878. 
This,  too,  Congress did when it enacted a penalty scheme that 
narrowed the class of death eligible defendants. 
 
Apart  from  these  constitutionally  necessary  legislative 
functions, "the Constitution does not require the jury to ignore 
other possible aggravating factors in the process of selecting, from 
among that class,  those defendants who will actually be sentenced 
to death."  Ibid.  To the contrary, "as long as th[e] information  
[supporting a non-statutory aggravating factor]  is relevant to the 
character of the defendant or the circumstances of the crime," 
consideration of non-statutory aggravating factors serves the useful 
purpose -- much like the consideration of non- statutory mitigating 
circumstances -- of ensuring an individualized sentencing 
determination that minimizes the risk of arbitrary and capricious  
action. Barclay,  463  U.S.  at  967  (Stevens,  J.,  concurring).  See 
also, Simmons v. South Carolina, 114 S Ct. 2187, 2193-2194 
(1994)~ Payne, 501 U.S. at 820-827 Zant, 462 U.S. at 875.  
"Although the Supreme Court has not required legislatures to 
permit jury consideration of all relevant aggravating factors in 
pursuing individualized sentencing, it clearly favors procedures 
that do 'not * * * impose unnecessary restrictions on the evidence 
that can be offered at [a capital] sentencing hearing'" because it is 
"'desirable for the jury to have as much information before it as 
possible when it makes the sentencing decision Pitera, 795 F. 
Supp. at 561, quoting, Gregg, 428 U.S. at 203-04. 
 
Federal prosecutors have traditionally had authority to bring to the 
sentencer's attention relevant information pertinent to a sentencing 
decision. And, unless expressly prohibited,  federal courts have 
traditionally "considered]  any and all information that might 
reasonably bear on the proper sentence for a particular defendant, 
given the crime committed."  Wasman v. United States, 468 U.S.  
559,  563  (1984).13 Thus,  the role of non-statutory aggravating 
factors in capital sentencing under the instant statute is "virtually 
the same" as the role of sentencing information in non-capital 
cases.  See Pitera, 795 F. Supp. at 562; Cooper, 754 F. Supp. at 
626.  Contrary to defendants' unfounded perception that non-
statutory aggravating factors perform the  constitutionally required 
role of narrowing the class of death-eligible defendants, the  
function  of  the  prosecutor  in  identifying  non-statutory 
aggravating  factors  under  Section  3593(a)  and  proving  their 
existence under Section 3593(c) is "an exercise in advocacy 
derived from the executive's discretion to prosecute, not the 
legislature's power to fix punishment."  Pitera, 795 F.Supp. at 563.  
See also, id. at 562 (because reliance on non-statutory aggravating 
factors "will,  in no small part,  reflect the prosecution's considered 
judgment as to why the case was a 'proper occasion' for serving a 
death penalty notice in the first place," such reliance is "an 
enforcement, not a legislative decision"); Walker, supra, at *11; 
Bradley,  880 F.  Supp. at 284. Because the allowance for non- 
statutory aggravating circumstances in the present capital statute 
involves "no delegation of legislative authority to the prosecutor" 
but simply allows the sentencer the benefit of the full range of 
information pertaining to the offense and the offender (Pitera, 795 
F.  Supp.  at  562),  it  does not  "implicate  the non-delegation 
doctrine."  Bradley, 880 F. Supp. at 284.  See also Walker, supra.   
 
We note that the court in Pretlow, 779 F. Supp. at 765-767, held 
that the provision for non-statutory aggravating factors involved a 
delegation of legislative authority to the Executive Branch.  
Accord, Davis, supra, at *2-3.  Nonetheless, comparing the instant  
"delegation"  with  the  more  extensive  delegation  of authority to 
fix sentences that was approved in Mistretta, the court  in Pretlow 
found that the Executive's exercise of this "delegated" authority 
was sufficiently informed by "intelligent principle[s]"  to pass 
constitutional muster. Those principles included (1)  the 
requirement that such factors be substantively limited to the 
circumstances of the crime and  the character of the accused;  (2)  
the availability of judicial review;  and  (3)  the requirement of 
notice.  Id. at 767-768.  See also, Davis, supra; Pitera, 795 F. Supp. 
at 562-563 ("even if this limited exercise of prosecutorial 
discretion were deemed to constitute a legislative delegation, its 
exercise is sufficiently circumscribed, both by the statute  and by  
judicial  review,  to  ensure  against  overbroad application").  
There is thus no support for defendants' contention that Congress 
impermissibly delegated its authority by allowing prosecutors to 
rely on non-statutory aggravating factors.  
 
C.  The Reliance On Non-Statutory Aggravating Factors Does Not 
Violate The Ex Post Facto Clause 
McVeigh next argues  (DE 454,  p.  39)  that Section 3592(c) 
violates the Ex Post Facto Clause by allowing non-statutory factors 
that are "applied retroactively to crimes committed before the 
aggravating circumstance is identified."  As the Supreme Court has 
made clear, however, the Ex Post Facto Clause is implicated only 
by "laws  that  'retroactively  alter  the  definition  of  crimes  or 
increase the punishment for criminal acts.'"  California Dept. of 
corrections v.  Morales,  115 S.  Ct.  1597,  1601  (1995),  quoting 
Collins v. Youngblood, 497 U.S. 37, 43 (1990).  Accord, Hatch v. 
State of Oklahoma,  58 F.3d 1447,  1463-1464  (lOth Cir.  1995). 
Aggravating factors, whether statutory or non-statutory in nature, 
"are not separate penalties or offenses" (Walton, 497 U.S. at 648) 
or "'elements' of any offense" (Jeffers, 497 U.S. at 782).  Rather, 
"the definition of [the] crimes" and the punishments available for 
40  
the offenses with which defendants are charged are contained in 
the various capital homicide statutes that were in existence at the 
time that the Murrah Federal Building was bombed.   
 
In Dobbert v. Florida, 432 U.S. 282, 293-294 (1977), the Court 
held that ex post facto safeguards are not triggered by procedural 
changes in a capital sentencing scheme that "simply alter the 
methods  in determining whether  the death penalty  [is]  to be 
imposed," but "effect[]  no change in the quantum of punishment 
attached to the crime" or the definition of the crime itself. Accord  
Hatch, 58 F.3d at 1463-1464; Evans v. Thompson, 881 F.2d 117, 
119-121 (4th Cir. 1989), cert. denied 497 U.S. 1010 (1990). 
Consistent with this principle, courts have held that the adoption of 
aggravating factors constitutes a procedural change in the method 
of determining whether a death sentence should be imposed, rather 
than a substantive change in the law respecting crimes and 
punishments, and, hence, that the retroactive application of such 
factors does not violate the Ex Post Facto Clause.  See Francis v. 
Dugger, 908 F.2d 696, 704 (llth Cir. 1990), cert. denied, 500 U.S. 
910 (1991); Jordon v. Walker, 681 F.2d 1067, 1079 (5th Cir. 
1982); Irving v. State, 441 So.2d 846, 852-853 (Miss. 1983), cert. 
denied, 470 U.S. 1059 (1985); State v. Coleman, 605 P.2d 1000, 
1012-1015 (Mont. 1979), cert. denied, 446 U.S. 970 (1980).  
Reliance on non- statutory aggravating factors is similarly proper 
under the Ex Post Facto Clause.  See Bradley, 880 F. Supp. at 284; 
Pitera, 795 F. SUPP. at 563-564.  
 
D.  Comparative Proportionality Review Is Not Required Merely 
Because Prosecutors Are Permitted To Rely Upon Non-Statutory 
Aggravating Factors 
McVeigh  alternatively  contends  (DE  454,  pp.  40-42)  that 
comparative proportionality review of any resulting death sentence 
is mandated, especially because the federal death penalty statute 
creates a "weighing" scheme.  Proportionality review, however, is 
required neither by the Constitution (see Pulley v. Harris, 465 U.S. 
37 (1984)) nor by federal statute.  See Bradley, 880 F. Supp. at 
284; Pretlow, 779 F. Supp. at 763 n. 2; Cooper, 754 F. Supp. at 
626; see also, Walker, supra, at *12 (comparative proportionality 
review permissible, but not mandated by statute);  Pitera, 795 F. 
Supp. at 567 (same). 
 
Contrary to McVeigh's claim, Zant, 462 U.S. at 879-880, 890, 
"does not compel a rule of mandatory proportionality [review] n 
whenever a statutory scheme permits consideration of non-
statutory aggravating factors.  See Walker, supra, at *12.  The 
Supreme Court made that precise point in Pulley v. Harris:  "[W]e 
did not hold  [in Zant]  that without comparative proportionality 
review the statute would be unconstitutional. To the contrary, we 
relied on the jury's finding of aggravating circumstances, not [on 
an appellate  court's] finding  of  proportionality,  as rationalizing 
the sentence.  Thus, the emphasis was on the constitutionally 
necessary narrowing function of statutory aggravating 
circumstances. Proportionality review was considered to be an 
additional safeguard against  arbitrarily  imposed death sentences,  
but  we certainly did not  hold that  comparative  review was 
constitutionally required." 465 U.S. at 50 (internal citations and 
footnote omitted). As we have  shown  above,  Section  3595  
ensures  that  federal  capital defendants will receive meaningful 
appellate review of their death sentences.  Zant  requires no more.  
See Walker, supra; Bradley, 880 F. Supp. at 284, Pitera, 795 F. 
Supp. at 559.   
 
E.  The Non-Statutory Aggravating Factor That Defendants Caused 
The Multiple Deaths of 169 Persons Is Valid 
Defendants contend (DE 454, pp. 44-45i DE 455, p. 27 n. 7) that 
the "multiple deaths" factor is unconstitutional because it fails to 
narrow the class of death-eligible defendants. This argument  
ignores the distinction between statutory aggravating factors that 
narrow death eligibility and non-statutory aggravating factors that 
aid the sentencer in determining whether a death- eligible 
defendant should be sentenced to death. "Eligibility" factors "play 
a constitutionally necessary function at the stage of the legislative 
definition: they circumscribe the class of persons eligible for the 
death penalty." Zant,  462 U.S.  at 878. In contrast, "selection" 
factors -- those factors that "determine[] whether a defendant 
eligible for the death penalty should in fact receive that sentence" -
- do not serve a narrowing function but instead allow "an 
individualized determination on the basis of the character of the 
individual and the circumstances of the crime." Tuilaepa, 114 S.Ct. 
at 2635, quoting Zant, 462 U.S. at 879.  See Simmons, 114 S. Ct. 
at 2193-2194; California v. Ramos, 463 U.S. 992,  1008  (1983);  
Barclay,  463  U.S.  at  967  (Stevens,  J., concurring).  Once the 
class of death-eligible defendants has been narrowed, the role of 
non-statutory aggravating factors in capital sentencing under the 
federal statutory scheme is "virtually the same" as the role of 
sentencing information in non-capital cases. See Pitera, 795 F. 
Supp. at 562, Cooper, 754 F. Supp. at 626.  
 
Under the instant capital sentencing scheme, the statutory 
aggravating factors listed in Section 3592(c)(  -(15) "involve[] a 
congressional narrowing of the class of persons eligible for the 
death penalty."  See Pitera, 795 F. Supp. at 559 (describing role of 
similar aggravating factors in 21 U.S.C. 848(n)(1)-(12)).  By 
contrast,  the non-statutory aggravating factors permitted under 
Section 3592(c) serve to "inform a jury's individualized sentencing 
decision." Ibid.  Thus, their constitutionally-permissible purpose is 
to ensure that the jury might consider "all relevant evidence" that 
"will assist [it] in making an individualized determination whether 
the defendant will be executed, n and not, as defendants would 
have it,  to further narrow the already narrowed class of death-
eligible defendants.  See Bradley, 880 F. Supp. at 285. 
 
The instant federal death penalty statute does not treat the 
commission of multiple homicides as a statutory aggravating 
factor. Nonetheless,  the fact that a defendant has committed 
multiple homicides is both a narrowing circumstance, in that it 
"appl[ies] only to a subclass of defendants" who have committed a 
capital crime  (Tuilaepa,  114 S. Ct. at 2635),  and highly relevant 
to a meaningful assessment of a  "defendant's moral culpability and 
blameworthiness," in that it permits consideration of "the specific 
harm caused by [a] defendant."  Payne, 501 U.S. at 825.  See 
Pulley v. Harris, 465 U.S. at 51-54 & n. 14 (upholding validity of 
capital sentencing scheme that relied on the commission of 
multiple murders as a statutory special circumstance); Pitera, 795 
F. Supp. 571, 577 (E.D.N.Y. 1992) (Pitera II) ("Since the 
government remains free to proffer  evidence  of  additional  
homicides  as  non-statutory aggravating factors, the court's ruling 
[precluding use of multiple homicides as a statutory aggravating 
factor]  in no way limits individualized sentencing"). 
 
Defendants'  additional argument that the  "multiple deaths" factor 
impermissibly duplicates the "if death results" element of the 
charged offenses must also be rejected.  Although Counts One, 
Two, and Three allege that the defendants' criminal conduct caused 
the deaths of more than 160 persons, a capital conviction on any of 
those counts merely requires that the jury find beyond a reasonable 
doubt  that  the  death  of  a  single  person  resulted  from  the 
defendants' commission of the offense.  Likewise, with respect to 
the eight first degree murder counts, the jury must find that the 
single victim identified in each separate count was murdered by the 
defendants.  Thus, it is only through the non-statutory aggravating 
factor pertaining to "multiple deaths" that the jury will be able to 
account for the true extent of human carnage caused by the 
defendants.  Moreover, even if the defendants are correct that the 
"multiple deaths" factor duplicates an offense element, Lowenfield 
permits such a result.  See supra, pp. 17-21.14  
 
F.  The Non-Statutory Aggravating Factor That Defendants Caused 
Serious Physical and Emotional Injuries Is Valid 
There is no merit to McVeigh's contention (DE 454, pp. 44-45) 
that the factor pertaining to the infliction of "serious physical and 
emotional injuries" is unconstitutionally vague.  It is well 
recognized that an offender's infliction of serious,  non-fatal 
injuries  on a  crime  victim  is  a  factor  that  aggravates  the 
seriousness of the offense, 15 and similar terms have been readily 
susceptible to definition. 16 Courts have consistently rejected 
claims that such terms are unconstitutionally vague.  See United 
States v.  Williams,  51 F.3d 1004,  l009-1010  (llth Cir.  1995); 
United States v. Fitzgerald, 882 F.2d 397, 398  (9th Cir. 1989); 
United States v. Protex Industries. Inc., 874 F.2d 740, 743 (lOth 
Cir. 1989).  As the court in Williams, 51 F.3d at 1010, stated in  
rejecting a void-for-vagueness  challenge  to  the  enhancement 
provision in the carjacking statute, 18 U.S.(  2119, for offenses 
resulting in "serious bodily injury":  "The fact that the statute 
'exposed  defendants  to  enhanced  penalties  based  on  legally 
significant factors does not make the statute void for vagueness."'  
The  instant  non-statutory  aggravating  factor  alleges  a 
traditional  sentencing  consideration  in  terms  that  possess  a 
"common-sense core of meaning" that a jury "should be capable of 
understanding." Tuilaepa,  114  S.  Ct.  at  2636. That  is 
particularly  true  since the factor identifies "maiming, 
disfigurement, and permanent disability"' as illustrative of the 
seriousness of the injuries to which it speaks.  Providing, as it does,  
"meaningful guidance to the sentencer, in the factor is not void for 
vagueness.  Cf. Walton, 497 U.S. at 654-655 (aggravating factor 
that required sentencer to determine whether "perpetrator 
inflict[ed] mental anguish or physical abuse before the victim's 
death's was not unconstitutionally vague). And,  "[i]f  further 
clarification  is  needed,  the  defendants  can  suggest  a  "jury 
instruction" at the appropriate time.  Davis, supra, at *2.  
 
G.  The Non-Statutory Aggravating Factor Engaged In Acts of 
Burglary Robbery and Theft to Facilitate The Charged Capital 
Offenses is Valid 
McVeigh contends  (DE 454,  pp.  45-47)  that the  "burglary, 
robbery, and theft" factor is constitutionally deficient because it 
relies on unadjudicated criminal conduct.  He is incorrect. 
 
The '"burglary, robbery, and theft" factor is constitutionally  
valid, as its existence "is relevant to [both] the character of the 
defendant [s] and the circumstances of the crime [s] ." Barclay, 463 
U.S. at 967 (Stevens, J., concurring); see also, Zant, 462 U.S. at 
878-879; Gregg, 428 U.S. at 189. Unlike extraneous criminal 
conduct, the "acts of burglary, robbery, and theft" cited in the death 
penalty notices were relied upon by defendants to "finance and 
otherwise facilitate the commission of the capital offense(s) 
charged in the indictment," and, for that reason, are circumstances 
that directly bear on defendants' bombing attack on the Murrah 
Federal Building. Moreover, the fact that the defendants resorted to 
"acts of burglary, robbery, and theft" to aid their eventual deadly 
bombing attack makes defendants more death-worthy than a killer 
who has never before caused or committed another criminal act, 
much less acts as serious as burglary and armed robbery. That 
being so, the fact that Congress has elected to treat some aspects of 
a capital defendant's criminal past as statutory aggravating factors 
that narrow the class of death-eligible defendants, does not 
preclude consideration of other aspects of a capital defendant's 
criminal history as selection factors to assist the sentencer in 
making an individual determination whether the death penalty is 
justified. See Bradley, 880 F. Supp. at 286.   
 
McVeigh's further claim (DE 454, pp. 46-47) that unadjudicated 
criminal conduct may not be considered during capital sentencing 
hearings is foreclosed by the Supreme Court's decision in Williams 
v. New York, 337 U.S. 241 (1949), and the Tenth Circuit's recent 
decision in Hatch, 58 F.3d at 1465-1466.  Contrary to McVeigh's 
assertion that "the Supreme Court has yet to resolve the 48 
constitutionality  of  admitting  unadjudicated  offenses  during the  
Court  lid  just  that  in capital  sentencing  proceedings, Williams. 
See also, Nichols v. United States, 114 S. Ct. 1921, 1928 (1994) 
("Sentencing courts have . . . considered a defendant's past criminal 
behavior, even if no conviction resulted from that behavior.  We 
have upheld the constitutionality of considering such conduct in 
Williams"); Payne, 501 U.S. at 820-821 (citing Williams for 
propositions that "the sentencing authority has always been free to 
consider a wide range of relevant material") In Hatch the Tenth 
Circuit expressly "follow[ed] Williams and join[ed] three other 
Circuit Courts in holding that the admission of evidence of 
unadjudicated offenses at a [capital] sentencing proceeding does 
not violate due process."  58 F.3d at 1465 (collecting cases).  See 
also, Bradley, 880 F. Supp. at 286-287 (approving consideration of 
unadjudicated conduct  as  a statutory aggravating  factor); Pitera 
II, 795 F. Supp. at 577 (same). 
 
H.  The Non-Statutory Aggravating Factor Pertaining To Victim 
Impact Is Valid 
The government's death penalty notices allege that, as a non- 
statutory aggravating factor,  "victim impact evidence" will be 
presented "concerning the effect of the defendant[s'] offense(s) on 
the victims and the victims' families. n McVeigh's argument that 
the "victim impact" factor is impermissible  (DE 454, p. 47)  is 
foreclosed by Payne, 501 U.S. at 827, which held that the Eighth 
Amendment permits consideration of "evidence about the victim 
and about  the  impact  of  the  murder  on  the  victim's  family"  in 
determining "whether or not the death penalty should be imposed. 
 
In line with Payne, Congress has expressly determined that victim 
impact  is  a  relevant  sentencing  factor  in  federal  capital 
proceedings.  18 U.S.C. 3S93(a)(2) .17 
 
CONCLUSION   
For the  above  reason,  defendants'  motions  to strike  the 
government's notices of its intention to seek the death penalty 
should be denied.  
 
RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED, 
PATRICK M. RYAN 
United States Attorney 
  
JOSEPH H. HARTZLER 
LARRY A. MACKEY 
Special Assistants United States Attorneys 
  
Robert J. Erickson 
Special Assistant United States Attorney 
 
 
 
l  In Gregg, the statute required state appellate courts to determine 
n [w]hether the sentence of death was imposed under the influence 
of passion, prejudice, or any other arbitrary factor[;] .  .  .  
[w]hether .  .  . the evidence supports the  [sentencer's] finding of a 
statutory aggravating circumstance  .  .  .[;]  and [w]hether the 
sentence of death is excessive or disproportionate to the penalty 
imposed in similar cases."  Ibid.  As described below, the instant 
review provisions are virtually identical to those in the Georgia 
statute, with the exception of Georgia's allowance for 
proportionality review, which is not constitutionally required. See 
Pulley v. Harris, 465 U.S. 37, 50-51 (1984).  
 
2  In light of McClesky, Mcveigh is plainly wrong(DE 454, p. 15) 
in reading Justice White's concurring opinion in Gregg as leaving 
open the possibility that the "standardless" prosecutorial discretion 
in determining whether the death penalty should be sought is 
subject to judicial review. 
 
3  3 Nichols'  attempt to extrapolate such a rule  from the holdings 
in Smith v. United States, 360 U.S. 1 (1959), and Sumner  v. 
Shuman, 483 U.S. 66  (1987), is far wide of the mark. Smith  
stands for the unremarkable proposition that a prosecution for an  
offense potentially punishable by death must be initiated by means  
of an indictment, even if the government does not intend to seek  
the death penalty upon conviction.  Shuman stands for the equally  
unremarkable proposition that a capital sentencing scheme 
mandating  a death sentence automatically upon conviction 
violates the Eighth  Amendment by foreclosing consideration of 
potentially mitigating  circumstances. Neither decision addresses 
whether aggravating  factors must be alleged in the indictment.  
Smith does, however,  support our position that it is for the 
government to determine  whether to seek the death penalty for 
capital crimes.  
 
Moreover,  as  criminal  forfeitures  must  be  alleged  in 
indictments by express operation of federal procedural rules, the  
decision in United States v. Seifuddin, 820 F.2d 1074, 1078 (9th  
Cir. 1987), on which Nichols relies, is irrelevant to the issue  
whether an indictment charging a capital offense must additionally  
allege, as a constitutional matter, the aggravating factors that  will 
later be relied upon to justify a sentence of death. 
 
4  Nichols  complains  (DE  455,  p.  21)  that  the  notices 
improperly allege "all the intent elements of  3591, without a  hint 
of which element the government will rely upon at trial. n The  
government  is  not  limited  to  reliance  on  a  single  mental  
culpability factor in establishing that death is a constitutionally  
proportionate punishment for a particular defendant.  See Flores,  
63 F.3d at 1370-1373 (affirming finding as to existence of multiple  
mental culpability factors).  McVeigh is also wrong (DE 454, pp.  
12-13 ) in arguing that the jury could give duplicative weight to  
multiple  mental  culpability  factors  in  the  event  that  the  
government is not required to elect a single factor for submission  
to the jury.  Unlike the capital sentencing scheme in Title 21, in  
which the mental culpability factors are treated as aggravating  
factors and are weighted by the jury  (see Flores,  supra),  the  
instant capital sentencing scheme does not categorize the mental 
culpability  factors  as  "aggravating  factors"  (see  18  U.S.C. 
3592(c)),  and the jury is permitted to weigh only aggravating  
factors "set forth in section 3592" and "any other" aggravating  
factors for which notice has been given. Consistent with the  
applicable capital sentencing scheme, our death penalty notices  
identify the mental culpability factors alleged as "preliminary  
factors, n but not as "aggravating factors." 
 
5  Defendants correctly note that such duplicative use of offense 
elements was held to be improper in State v. Middlebrooks,  840 
S.W.2d 317  (Tenn.  1992),  cert.  dismissed,  114 S.  Ct.  651  
(1993),  and State v. Cherry,  257 S.E.2d 551 (N.C.  1979), cert.  
denied, 446 U.S. 941 (1980).  These cases have not been followed 
by  the federal courts.  See Deputy v. Taylor, 19 F.3d at 1500-
1502;  Snell v. Lockhart, 14 F.3d at 1305.  
 
6  United States v. Cheely, 36 F.3d 1439 (9th Cir. 1994), is not to 
the contrary.  In Cheely, a prosecution that predated the enactment 
of 18 U.S.C. 3591, et seq., the Ninth Circuit held that  the capital 
penalty provisions applicable to the mail bomb offenses  in  18  
U.S.C.  844(d)  and 1716 were constitutionally defective  because  
they  did  not  limit  the  category  of  death-eligible  defendants to 
those who actually intended to kill.  36 F.3d at 1445  & n. 15.  
Unlike in Cheely, the instant capital sentencing statute  requires a 
threshold finding that a capital defendant intended to  kill (18 
U.S.C. 3591(a)) and further provides detailed procedures  for 
channeling the jury's discretion.  
 
7  The legislative history of the federal death penalty statute and its 
"weapons of mass destruction" provision buttresses  this 
conclusion. Before their ultimate adoption as part of the  Violent 
Crime Control and Law Enforcement Act of 1994, Pub. L. 103-  
322  (Sept.  13,  1994),  Congress repeatedly considered bills  
containing "weapons of mass destruction" provisions whose 
offense  language was identical to that adopted in Section 2332a 
and capital  sentencing provisions that relied upon the commission 
of a "weapons  of mass destruction" offense as an aggravating 
factor; however,  these bills often varied in their placement of such 
identically-  worded "weapons of mass destruction" provisions 
within Title 18's  "terrorism" chapter, with some bills placing the 
offense a in  newly-created section "2339"  (See 139 Cong. Rec. 
H10230 (Nov. 19,  1993); 137 Cong. Rec. H7950 (Oct. 16, 1991); 
137 Cong. Rec. S9991  (July 15, 1991)) and others placing it in a 
newly-created section  "2339A" (see 139 Cong. Rec. S10407 (Aug. 
4, 1993); 139 Cong. Rec.  S296 (Jan. 21, 1993); 138 Cong. Rec. 
S2690 (Mar. 3, 1992)).  This  history reveals both the consistency 
of Congress' purpose to treat  the "weapons of mass destruction" 
offense that now is codified as  Section 2332a as a statutory 
aggravating factor and the likely  reason for Congress' miscitation 
to a non-existence "section 2339." 25  
 
8  As the Court observed in Tuilaepa, in the post-Furman era, it has 
found only a few sentencing factors to be unconstitutionally  
vague, primarily those involving pejorative adjectives describing  
the capital crime as a whole. 114 S.Ct. at 2636. See. e.q.,  Maynard 
v. Cartwright, 486 U.S. 356, 363-364 (1988) (whether murder  was 
"especially heinous, atrocious, or cruel"); Godfrey v. Georgia,  446 
U.S. 420, 427-429 (1980)  (whether murder was "outrageously or  
wantonly vile, horrible, or inhuman").  Sentencing considerations  
of this nature are not at issue here.  Compare Proffitt, 428 U.S.  at 
255-258 (phrase "conscienceless or pitiless crime which [wa]s  
unnecessarily torturous  to  the victim"  not unconstitutionally  
vague); Arave v. Creech, 113 S.Ct. at 1543 (phrase "utter disregard  
for human life" not unconstitutional when narrowed to mean a 
"cold-  blooded, pitiless slayer"). 
 
9  McVeigh attempts to distinguish Flores on the ground that the 
Title 21 capital sentencing scheme requires proof of two  
aggravating factors, while the Title 18 capital sentencing scheme  
only requires proof of one aggravating factor.  DE 454, p. 31 n.  
25.  Whether the Title 21 procedures require a greater degree of  
narrowing is irrelevant to the question whether the "substantial  
planning and premeditation"  factor is sufficiently definite in  
meaning to pass constitutional muster. Moreover,  the  second  
aggravating factor that must be found under the Title 21 capital  
sentencing scheme replicates exactly the mental culpability finding  
that must be preliminarily made under 18 U.S.C. 3591(a)(2). 
 
10  Nor is there merit to Nichols' contention that the term n 
terrorism" makes the aggravator vague. Defendants are charged  
with violating the weapons of mass destruction statute, 18 U.S.C.  
2332a,  which is contained in the chapter of the criminal code  
entitled "Terrorism," and the terms "international terrorism" (18  
U.S.C. 2331(1)) and "act of terrorism" (18 U.S.C. 3077) are further  
defined in Title 18. 
 
1l  The regulation was issued by the Attorney General on May 18,  
1994. The death penalty provisions of the Violent Crime Control 
and Law Enforcement Act of 1994 were enacted into law on 
September 13, 1994. See Pub. L. 103-322, Title VI,  60002(a).  
McVeigh is wrong in stating that the regulation was promulgated 
after the enactment of the death penalty statute and in suggesting 
that it was meant to expand the scope of Section 3592(c)(14). 
 
12  Defendant McVeigh also complains about a lack of notice 
concerning the identities of the homicide victims who qualify as 
"law enforcement officers" under Section 3592(c)(14).  Although 
his lack-of-notice complaint does not go to the constitutional 
validity of Section 3592(c)(14),  we note that the eight murder 
victims listed in Counts Four through Eleven are includable, as all 
eight murder victims are identified as  "special agents"  employed 
by specific law enforcement agencies and are alleged to have been 
killed "while they were engaged in or on account of the 
performance of their official duties as law enforcement officers. 
 
13  See Roberts v. United States, 445 U.S. 552, 556 (1980); United 
States v. Grayson, 438 U.S. 41, 45-50 (1978); United States v. 
Tucker, 404 U.S. 443, 446 (1972); Williams v. New York, 337 
U.S. 241, 247 (1949). 
 
14  In like vein, defendants argue (DE 454, pp. 44-47; DE 455, p. 
27 n. 7) that the three other non-statutory aggravating factors 
alleged in the death penalty notices are unconstitutional because 
they also fail to narrow the class of death-eligible defendants and 
duplicate  matters  charged  in  the  indictment. Defendants' 
"narrowing"  and  "duplication"  challenges  to  these  other non-
statutory aggravating factors must fail for the reasons that their 
challenges to the "multiple deaths" factor fail: non-statutory 
aggravating factors need not further narrow the already narrowed 
class of death-eligible defendants, and Lowenfield makes clear that 
aggravating factors may permissibly duplicate matters alleged in 
the indictment. 
 
15  See, e.q., 18 U.S.C. lll(b)  ("bodily injury"); 18 U.S.C. 
113(a)(6)  &  (7) ("resulting  in  serious  bodily  injury"  or  
"substantial bodily injury");  18 U.S.C.  2119  ("serious bodily  
injury"); U.S.S.G. Guidelines Manual  2A2.1(b)  ("permanent or  
life-threatening bodily injury" or in "serious bodily injury"); i .  at 
2A2.2  (same)i  i .  at 2A4.1  (same);  id.  at 5K2.2  ("insignificant 
physical injury"); id. at  5K2.3  (sychological  injury  much  more  
serious  than  normally  resulting  from  the  commission of the 
offense"). 
 
16  See, e.q., 18 U.S.C. 113(b)  (defining "substantial bodily 
injury"  and  "serious  bodily  injury");  18  U.S.C.  1365(g)(3) 
(defining "serious bodily injury"); U.S.S.C. Guidelines Manual 
lA1.1, Commentary, Note l(h) & (j)  (defining "permanent or life-  
threatening bodily injury" and "serious bodily injury").  See also  
United States v. Talamante, 981 F.2d 1153, 1158 & n. 8 (lOth Cir.  
1992)  (favorably citing jury instruction that "was identical, in  
pertinent part, to the guideline definition of permanent or life-  
threatening injury[]  and included obvious disfigurement as an  
example of serious injury"), cert. denied, 113 S. Ct. 1876 (1993). 
 
17  In addition, Nichols is wrong in asserting (DE 455, p. 27 n.  7)  
that the "victim impact"  factor duplicates the "serious  physical 
and emotional injury" factor.  The "victim impact" factor  focuses 
on "each [homicide] victim's 'uniqueness as an individual  human 
being' . . . whose death represents a unique loss to society  and in 
particular to his family."  Payne, 501 U.S. at 823, 825.  By  
contrast,  the  "serious  physical  and emotional  injury"  factor  
focuses on the serious, albeit non-fatal,  injuries sustained by  
many of those who survived the deadly bombing.
