<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<P>In this Sept. 28, 1995 brief, the prosecution in the Oklahoma City bombing trials proposes measures such as asking the jurors to "avoid all media . . . that might possibly provide information about the case," and to "understand that they must avoid social situations that might lead to discussions of the case . . . some jurors might have no alternative but to avoid certain acquaintances or even relatives." as an alternative to sequestration of the jury.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<PRE>
IN THE UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT 
FOR THE WESTERN DISTRICT OF OKLAHOMA 
 
UNITED STATES OF AMERICA, 
 
Plaintiff, 
 
v. 
 
TIMOTHY JAMES McVEIGH 
 
and 
 
TERRY LYNN NICHOLS, 
 
Defendants. 
 
 
No. CR 95-110-A 
 
 
GOVERNMENT'S PROPOSED SEQUESTRATION 
ALTERNATIVES  
 
 
This brief responds to the Court's August 21, 1995 order directing 
that the parties propose measures that may be used in lieu of 
traditional sequestration during the trial of this case.  
 
The United States shares the Court's concern that the jury be 
insulated from extraneous influence, yet spared the hardship of 
lengthy sequestration.  Accordingly, the government proposes that 
the Court consider the following alternatives: (a) empaneling an 
anonymous jury; (b) directing the United States Marshall Service 
to establish measures to protect jurors' identities and outside 
contacts; (c) requiring prospective jurors to agree, in lieu of 
sequestration, to dramatic alteration of their reading, viewing and 
leisure activities; and (d) ordering all persons, including media 
representatives, to avoid any contact with jurors concerning the 
case.  The Court should also make the traditional inquiries and give 
the usual admonitions that the jury avoid outside influences.  
 
If it becomes apparent at any time that these measures will be or 
are insufficient, then the Court can consider sequestration as a last 
resort. In that event,  the United States respectfully suggests that 
this Court consider juror-friendly housing.   
 
I.  MEASURES IN LIEU OF SEQUESTRATION. 
 
a.  Anonymous Jury 
 
A publicly anonymous jury might substantially reduce the risk of 
jury intimidation and contamination. Federal courts have 
repeatedly endorsed the use of anonymous juries in cases 
presenting some combination of a high degree of publicity ;which 
increased the likelihood that jurors' names would become public 
and that they would be subjected to improper contacts), charges 
involving serious violent crimes,  and the prospect of significant 
penalties upon conviction.  E.q., United States v. Edmond, 52 F.3d 
1080, 1091-1094 (D.C. Cir. 1995); United States v. Ross, 33 F.3d 
1507, 1520 (11th  Cir. 1994), cert. denied, 115 S.Ct. 2558 (1995); 
United States v. Vario, 943 F.2d 236, 240  (2d Cir. 1991), cert. 
denied,  502 U.S. 1036 (1992); United States v. Shakur, 623 F. 
Supp. 1, 3-4 (S.D.N.Y. 1983).  All these factors are present in this 
highly-publicized case involving a terrorist incident of 
unprecedented violence in which defendants face lengthy prison 
sentences and possibly the death penalty. Selection of anonymous 
jurors would not alter the level playing field because the 
government would be entitled to no more (and no less) information 
about prospective jurors.  
 
If the government ultimately seeks the death penalty, defendants 
may be entitled under 18 U.S.C. Section 3432 to the names and 
"place[s] of abode" of the venirepersons three days before trial. 
The statute is silent concerning disclosure of the list to the 
government, but presumably that disclosure would occur no later 
than three days before trial as well.  
 
Although the apparent purpose of Section 3432 is to provide the 
parties    a capital case an opportunity to investigate the 
background of potential  jurors, the statute does  not  grant 
unqualified access to a venire list.  Indeed, it eliminates any right 
to the list where "the court finds by a preponderance of the 
evidence that providing the list may jeopardize the life or safety of 
any person."  Even if the Court ultimately were to furnish the 
venire list to the parties under section 3432,  nothing in the statute 
precludes a protective order barring the parties from disclosing any 
names on the list to third parties.  See W.D. Ok. Local Rule 
27(H)(5) (Court may issue special order" in "highly publicized" 
cases directing that the names and addressee of jurors or 
prospective jurors not be publicly released except as required by 
statute, and that no photograph be taken or sketch made of any 
juror within the environs of the  Court").[fn 1]  Cf.,  Breechen v. 
Reynolds, 41 F.3d 1343, 1351 (10th Cir. 1994)  (discussing 
Sheppard v. Maxwell, 384 U.S. 333 (1966),  where trial court  
failed to provide fair trial because, among other things, it took 
inadequate steps to avoid  "publication of potential juror's names  
and addresses  allowing  the  public  to  contact potential  jurors 
pretrial"), cert. denied, 115 S.Ct. 2564 (1995).  
 
To enable some limited investigation prior to jury selection, the 
Court could fashion a procedure whereby the parties obtained the 
Court's approval ex parte to disclose names on the list to certain 
named people and certified that those people would not further 
disclose the names.  Of course, to protect jurors' privacy and rights 
to be free from harassment or tampering,  any investigation of 
venirepersons beyond discussion with court-approved persons or 
examination of pre-existing records should be conducted solely 
under court supervision.  See 2 Charles Alan Wright, Federal 
Practice and Procedure Criminal Section 382 at 344 (1982) ("the 
impartiality of jurors should be tested under the control of the court 
rather than by the unsupervised activity of investigators with all the 
undesirable possibilities  of intimidation and jury tampering which 
such surveillance inevitably presents") (internal quotations 
omitted); see also id. n.4 ("'In those cases where it appears 
necessary to conduct  a pretrial investigation of the background of 
jurors, investigatory methods of the lawyer should neither harass 
nor unduly embarrass potential jurors or invade their privacy and, 
whenever possible, should be restricted  to  an  investigation  of  
records and  sources  of information already in existence'") 
(quoting 1980 edition of ABA Standards for Criminal Justice).  
 
In empaneling an anonymous jury,  the Court could assign a 
number to each prospective juror, who would be known only by 
that number throughout voir dire and the remainder of trial.  This 
procedure has been successful in other highly publicized criminal 
cases.  Note, Prejudicial Publicity Surrounding a Criminal Trial: 
What a Trial Court Can Do to Ensure a Fair Trial in the Face of a 
"Media Circus", 26 Suffolk U.L.R. 1063, 1076 (1992) (describing 
how "assigned numbers shielded the identities of prospective jurors 
from the press" in federal trial of John DeLorean).  
 
b.  Measures to Protect Juror Privacy and Security.  
 
Obviously, it serves little purpose to empanel an anonymous jury 
without instituting measures to protect the jurors privacy and 
security outside the courthouse . The Marshal's Service is fully 
capable of devising measures to limit outsiders from, learning the 
identities of the jurors. Similarly, the Marshal's Service has well-
established practices to protect jurors from unauthorized outside 
contacts. In light of the media attention focused on this case and 
the many outside interests that might try to influence the verdict, 
the Marshal's Service should employ all necessary measures to 
protect jurors from such contacts. To detail those measures in a 
public pleading, however, would seriously reduce the effectiveness 
of those measures. Accordingly, the government recommends that 
the Marshal's Service  privately  convey  its recommendations to 
the Court regarding juror privacy and security .  
 
c. Jurors' Agreement To Alert Their Activities.  
 
Most jurors presumably would prefer to live at home rather than be 
sequestered. That benefit cannot come without cost. Jurors 
typically are admonished to avoid reading or listening to reports 
about the case.  See, e.g., W.D. Ok. Local Rule 7(H)(3). Here, 
however, that simple admonition may not suffice. Instead, it will 
likely be necessary that jurors agree to avoid all media -- print and 
electronic, including computer -- that might possibly provide 
information about the case.  This requirement would restrict juror's 
access to virtually all commercial television and ratio  because  
news  "teasers" can and regularly do interrupt scheduled 
programming.  
 
This restriction might prevent jurors from watching or listening  to  
commercial  television or  radio, or to visiting establishments 
where televisions or radios are turned on, while restricting them to 
pre-recorded programs and tapes.  It would likely also prevent 
jurors from reading or even picking up any current daily 
newspaper, as the headlines are likely to offer news of the case. 
The Marshal's Service, however, might be able to provide jurors 
daily newspapers or magazines from which articles relating to the 
case have been clipped. It may also be possible to provide taped 
versions of favorite programming or sporting events;, edited to 
guard against any references to the case.  
 
Jurors who could not abide by the necessary restrictions on their 
outside reading, viewing and listening practices, or by an 
admonition not to discuss the case with family and friends, should 
be encouraged to reveal themselves during voir dire so as to avoid 
problems later. Empaneled jurors should understand that they must 
avoid social situations that might lead to discussions of the case. 
To comply with the Court's admonition, some jurors might have no 
alternative but to avoid certain acquaintances or even relatives.  
 
d.  Media and Third Party Restrictions 
 
The  United States does not advocate  ~he constitutionally 
questionable device of imposing restrictions on the media's out-of-
court coverage  of  the crime and trial. Cf. Nebraska Press 
Association v. Stewart, 427 U.S. 539 11976).  Nor does the United 
States advocate at present the imposition of a "gag order" upon 
counsel, investigators or witnesses. Such an order may be 
constitutional if the Court were to find that out-of-court speech was 
substantially likely to interfere with a fair trial. See, e.g., Gentile v. 
State Bar of Nevada, 501 U.S. 1030, 1075 (1991); United States v. 
Cutler, 58 F.3d 825, 835-937 (2d Cir. 1995); Cf. Sheppard v. 
Maxwell, 384 U.S. 333, 361    66) ("the trial court might well have 
proscribed extrajudicial statements by any lawyer, party, witness, 
or court official which divulged prejudicial matters . . . concerning 
the merits of the cases) (dictum). See also W.D. Ok. Local Rule 27 
(E) (precluding lawyers from making or authorizing public 
statement during trial "if there is a reasonable likelihood that such 
dissemination will interfere with a fair trial, except that the lawyer 
or law firm may quote from or refer without comment to public 
records of the court in the case"). It is clear, however, that third 
parties, including the press, can be directed at the appropriate time 
not to contact venirepersons or jurors. There is no First 
Amendment right to contact such persons if doing so "would 
influence the jury."  See United States v. Ogle, 613  F.2d 233,  243  
(10th Cir.  1979)  (affirming obstruction of justice conviction of 
individual who distributed to sitting juror "A Handbook for Jurors" 
describing concept of jury nullification), cert. denied, 449 U.S. 825 
(1980).  
 
II.  NON-TRADITIONAL SEQUESTRATION. 
 
To the extent the above and other measures prove inadequate to 
ensure juror integrity, the Court could consider a non-traditional, 
modified form of sequestration. The hardships and isolation that 
jurors suffer during sequestration can be tempered by housing 
jurors in a facility that will enable their families to join them 
during their jury service or at least on weekends. The government 
proposes that the Court invite the parties to identify suitable 
facilities in the area of the trial.  The criteria for a suitable facility 
should include, among other factors, proximity to the courthouse; 
ability to protect jurors from outside influences; cost; sufficient 
space to accommodate families; availability of day-care,  medical  
services, religious services,  and  postal delivery; and proximity to 
leisure activities and entertainment. Although ultimately it may be 
.impossible to keep the location of the jurors secret, the parties 
should be directed to submit under seal their recommendations and 
supporting information for housing that meets those criteria once it 
is finally decided where trial is to be held.  
 
CONCLUSION 
 
The United States agrees with the Court's implicit view that 
traditional sequestration of jurors is a procedure of last resort that 
should be considered only after less restrictive alternatives have 
been exhausted. Any discussion of such alternatives is necessarily 
somewhat tentative given that trial is months away in a location 
not finally determined.  Nonetheless, there are certain general areas 
of concern, and possible steps to be taken in response, that the 
United States sought to identify in this brief.  
 
Respectfully submitted, 
 
PATRICK M. RYAN 
U.S. Attorney  
 
JOSEPH H. HARTZLER 
LARRY A. MACKEY 
SEAN CONNELLY 
Special Assistant U.S. Attorneys 
 
/s/JEROME A. HOLMES 
Assistant U.S. Attorney 
10 W. Park Avenue, Suite 400 
Oklahoma City, Oklahoma  73102 
(405) 231-5281  
 
CERTIFICATE OF SERVICE 
 
This is to certify that on this 28th day of September 1995, true 
copies of this brief were served on:  1) Counsel for Timothy James 
McVeigh:   Stephen Jones, Esq. and Robert Nigh, Esq.;  114 East 
Broadway, Suite 1100; Post Office Box 412; Enid, Oklahoma 
73702-0472 (By telecopier and mail); and 2)  Counsel for Terry 
Lynn Nichols:  Michael E. Tigar, Esq., and Ronald G. Woods, 
Esq., Mid-America Tower,  Suite 1620,  Oklahoma City,  
Oklahoma  73102  (By telecopier and mail).   
 
/s/JEROME A. HOLMES 
Assistant U.S. Attorney 
 
 
Endnotes 
 
1. The anonymous jury cases make clear that no law requires 
public dissemination of juror names and addresses.  In re Baltimore 
Sun Co., 841 F.2d 74, 75 (4th Cir. 1988), on the other hand, held 
that [a]fter a jury has been seated, ... the names of [seated and 
unseated venirepersons] are just as much of the public record as 
any other part of the case, and we think so also are  their addresses 
in order to identify them."  The court "emphasize[d] that we do not 
deal here with a situation  in which there existed realistic threats of 
violence or jury corruption." Id. at 76 n.5.  
