<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A>
<P>Hundreds of documents have been filed in the investigation of the bombing of the Oklahoma City Federal Building, many of which have been sealed or released to the public in revised form. Several area television stations and journalistic societies have entered this motion to unseal documents and to require hearing on the sealing of future documents. In this Oct. 2, 1995 motion, the "Media Group" alleges that proper procedures were not followed in sealing the documents.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<PRE>
IN THE UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT 
FOR THE WESTERN DISTRICT OF OKLAHOMA 
 
 
UNITED STATES OF AMERICA, 
 
Plaintiff, 
 
v. 
 
TIMOTHY JAMES McVEIGH, 
and TERRY LYNN NICHOLS, 
 
Defendants. 
 
 
Case No. CR-95-110-A 
 
 
MEDIA GROUP'S MOTION TO OPEN SEALED 
DOCUMENTS, TO REQUIRE CAUSE BEFORE SEALING 
DOCUMENTS AND FOR ACCESS TO DOCKET SHEETS  
 
FOI Oklahoma,Inc., the Associated Press, The Daily Oklahoman, 
The Tulsa World, KFOR-TV Channel 4, KWTV Channel 9, KJRH 
Channel 2 (Tulsa), Society of Professional Journalist Oklahoma 
City Chapter and Society of Professional Journalist Eastern 
Oklahoma Chapter (hereinafter "Media Group") move this Court to 
enter an appropriate order respecting documents sealed in this and 
companion cases.  
 
In support of this motion, Media Group states that:  
 
1.   Media Group consists of a public interest association, members 
of the print and broadcast media and associations of journalists  
who have  a  legitimate interest  in observing  and reporting on the 
criminal proceedings arising from the April 19, 1995, Oklahoma 
City bombing.  Media group has standing to request access to these 
court documents under the First Amendment to the United States 
Constitution.  
 
2.   The docket sheets maintained for U.S. v. McVeigh, Case No. 
M-95-98. U.S. v. Nichols, Case No. M-95-105, and the above-
referenced case (combined), have sequential numbering gaps. 
Many filed documents are not identified with either a number or a 
brief description.  
 
3.   Media Group has not received notice of any motion to seal the 
documents and therefore has had no opportunity to object. Media 
Group is not aware of any order finding that the government 
interest in sealing the documents outweighs the public's recognized 
First Amendment right of access to said documents, or a finding 
that the Court considered less restrictive means to sealing 
documents, such as providing public access to documents in a 
redacted form.  
 
4.   As more specifically set forth in the accompanying brief, the 
First  Amendment  requires  notice  to  the public  and  an 
opportunity for the public to be heard and object to closed 
proceedings or to the sealing of documents, and the moving party 
has the burden of demonstrating a compelling interest that would 
be irreparably harmed by disclosure.  
 
5.   The documents in this case were sealed without proper 
procedures and contrary to the constitutional standards.  
 
6.   A similar motion was filed last Thursday (September 28) by 
Combined Communications Corporation of Oklahoma. See 
"Motion of Combined Communications Corporation of Oklahoma 
to Open Sealed Documents and to Direct Applicable Procedures 
for Further Orders Sealing Documents" (docket entry no. 365) and 
"Brief Supporting Motion of Combined Communications 
Corporation of Oklahoma to Open Sealed Documents and to Direct 
Applicable Procedures for Further Orders Sealing Documents" 
(docket entry no. 366).  
 
WHEREFORE, Media Group respectfully moves the Court to 
issue an order: (1) unsealing all documents previously filed under 
seal in the above-referenced and companion cases, (2) granting 
Media Group and the public the opportunity to challenge any 
further motions to seal documents or close proceedings in this 
case,and (3) directing the court clerk to provide public access to a 
complete copy of the docket sheets in the above-referenced and 
companion cases. Alternatively,Media Group moves this court to 
enter an order requiring parties to show cause why sealed 
documents should remain sealed and to release to the public 
thereafter as appropriate the sealed documents or redacted versions 
of sealed documents.  
 
MICHAEL MINNIS & ASSOCIATES, P.C. 
 
By: /s/ Michael Minnis, OBA #6251 
David McCullough, OBA #10898 
3160 Liberty Tower 
100 North Broadway 
Oklahoma City, OK  73102 
(405) 235-7686 
 
