1988)  
 
Times Mirror Co. v. U.S. 873 F.2d 1210 (9th Cir. 1989)  
 
U.S. v. Gerena, 703 F.Supp 211 (D.Com. 1989), judgment eff. 
U.S. v. Suarez, 880 F.2d 626 (2nd Cir. 1989)  
 
U.S. v. McVeigh, M-95-98-H 
 
U.S. v. Nichols, M-95-105-H 
 
United States v. Dorfman, 690 F.2d 1230 (7th Cir. 1982)  
 
United States v. Rosenthal, 763 F.2d 1291 (11th Cir. 1985)  
 
Washington Post Co. v. Hughes, 923 F.2d 324 (4th Cir.), cert. 
denied. 500 U.S. 944 (1991)  
 
 
BRIEF IN SUPPORT OF MOTION TO OPEN SEALED 
DOCUMENTS AND TO FOLLOW PROCEDURES BEFORE 
SEALING DOCUMENTS  
 
FOI Oklahoma Inc., the Associated Press, The Daily Oklahoman, 
The Tulsa World, KFOR TV Channel 4, KWTV Channel 9, KJRH 
Channel 2 (Tulsa), Society of Professional Journalist Oklahoma 
City Chapter and Society of Professional Journalist Eastern 
Oklahoma Chapter (hereinafter "Media Group") have moved this 
Court to enter an order respecting documents previously filed 
under seal in the above-referenced and related cases[fn 1] and for 
other relief.  
 
INTRODUCTION 
 
The bombing of the Murrah Federal Building constituted an attack 
on the American people and our form of government. Probably no 
event since the assassination of President John F. Kennedy has had 
such an impact on the American psyche. Bringing to justice those 
responsible is the desire of all Americans. Justice in this country 
means, at an a minimum that the governmental process of 
punishing  those responsible  for  this  heinous  crime  is  above 
reproach. This means that all citizens must consistently review the 
process to insure government does not overstep the boundaries 
imposed by the Constitution of the United States of America. This 
means the process should and must be open.  
 
Already over 100 documents filed in the matter have been sealed 
and dual docket sheets (one for the public and one "not public") 
established. This has created an aura of secrecy about filed 
pleadings in a criminal trial that may be unprecedented. The 
massive closure is particularly suspect because the sealing was 
accomplished without  any record of  good cause shown  for  the 
sealing.[fn 2]  
 
At a minimum the court should hold an appropriate hearing to 
determine if the sealed documents should remain sealed and should 
release redacted versions of the documents where appropriate. The 
court should also direct the court clerk to maintain complete docket 
sheets open for public inspection that reflect all court activity.  
 
ARGUMENT AND AUTHORITIES 
 
The public and press have a constitutional right of access to court 
proceedings and records relating to them, and such proceedings 
and  records  are  presumptively  open. Press-Enterprise Co. v. 
Superior Court, 478 U.S. 1, 106 S.Ct. 2735, 92 L.Ed.2d 1 (1986).  
 
1.   Standing to Challenge the Sealing Order  
 
The petitioners have standing to file this motion. Indeed,the right 
of the media to contest limitations on access to judicial records and 
proceedings is recognized as being of constitutional dimension. 
Globe Newspapers Co. v. Superior Court,457 U.S. 596,699 n.25, 
102 S.Ct. 2613, 73 L.Ed.2d 248 (1982). ("[R]epresentatives of the 
press and general public must be given an opportunity to be heard 
on the question of their exclusion.")  (internal quotations and 
citations omitted.) See also In re Knoxville News-Sentinel Co., 
Inc., 723 F.2d 470, 475  (6th Cir.  1983)  ("The importance of the 
rights involved and interests served by those rights require that the 
public and press be given an opportunity to respond before being  
denied  their presumptive  right  of  access  to  judicial records.") 
Consistent with this principle, the Sixth Circuit has held that the 
media has standing to challenge even gag orders directed to the 
parties  and their counsel, since  such orders interfere with the 
media's ability to gather news,the complement to the First 
Amendment right to publish news. CBS, Inc. v. Young, 522 F.2d 
234 (6th Cir. 1975).  
 
2.   Documents were sealed contrary to the public right of access.  
 
To seal court records consistent with the First Amendment, the 
public must be given an opportunity to object and the court must 
make findings after a hearing that: (a) a compelling interest will be 
irreparably harmed if the public has access to the documents; (b) 
no alternatives to closure are reasonably available to preserve that 
interest; and (c) the closure order will be effective in 
accomplishing  its intended  purpose.  Press-Enterprise Co. v. 
Superior Court, 464 U.S. at 510.  
 
In this case, this procedure was not followed. The public was not 
given prior notice and no public documentation exists that any 
party attempted to establish the necessary predicate or that the 
court made the findings necessary to justify closure.  
 
The principal targets of the criminal investigation have been 
indicted. The investigation leading to the indictments has already 
received  pervasive  media coverage.  Potential  targets  of  the 
investigation  have already  been  put  on  notice,  or  have  been 
identified in other media coverage of the investigation. Release of 
the search warrants  and related records  is  thus  unlikely to 
interfere with any ongoing investigation. The public has a right to 
examine  the  actions  of  its  law  enforcement officers  in 
investigating these crimes. See, e.g., Gunn, 855 F.2d at 576-77 
(Heaney, J., concurring and dissenting) (noting that once there is  
extensive press coverage of an investigation, "[T]he benefit to be 
gained by continuing secrecy is negligible as compared to the 
public benefit that would be gained by disclosure.").   
 
3.   If the Proper Procedures Had Been Followed, the Finding 
Could Not Be Made for the Seal Documents Identified.  
 
Petitioners cannot identify all documents under seal because the 
"public" docket sheet is incomplete.[fn 3] Among the documents 
sealed are voucher and time records,[fn 4] defendants' bomb site 
inspection  documents, defendants' financial affidavits, probable 
cause affidavits and search warrants obtained by federal law 
enforcement agents in connection with the investigation into the 
bombing of the Murrah Federal Building in Oklahoma City. These 
documents are judicial records and, therefore, should be unsealed.  
 
The Rules for the Western District of Oklahoma state that financial 
affidavits are open.  "All statements made by a person in 
requesting counsel or during the inquiry into eligibility shall be 
either (i) by affidavit sworn to before the Court, a Court Clerk or 
Deputy, or a Notary Public, or (ii) under oath in open Court." Rule 
40 (E)(l)(a).  
 
The documents reflecting payments made under the Criminal 
Justice Act, 18 U.S.C. 3006A are also open to the public. U.S. v. 
Gerena, 703 F.Supp 211 (D.Com. 1989), judgment affirmed, U.S. 
v. Suarez, 880 F.2d 626 (2nd. Cir. 1989); see also U.S. v. Coniam, 
574 F.8 Supp. 615, 616 (D.Comm 1983).  
 
Fed. R. Crim. P. 41(g) requires magistrates to file with the clerk of 
the district court warrants,the returns and all supporting 
documents, These filings render those documents "judicial records" 
to which a presumption of openness attaches. In re Search Warrant 
for Second Floor Bedroom, 489 F.Supp. 207, 212, n.1 (D.R.I. 
1980).  
 
A qualified First Amendment right of access to search warrant- 
related documents has been recognized in some circuits (e.g., In re 
Search for Secretarial Area Outside Office of Gunn, 855 F.2d 569, 
573 (8th Cir. 1988) (Gunn I)); Certain Interested Individuals v. 
Pulitzer Publishing Co., 895 F.2d 460 (8th Cir. 1990), cert. denied, 
Pulitzer Pub. Co. v. Certain Interested Individuals, 498 U.S. 880, 
right to a fair trial can outweigh the public's right of access to 
search warrant documents. Id. at 328-29;  see also In re Search 
Warrants, 18 Med.L.Rep. 1095, 1100 (D.D.C. 1990) ("once an 
individual  is so indicted, the public has a legitimate interest in 
information contained in the affidavits in support of the search 
warrant and oral and wire intercepts which led to the indictment. a 
) .  
 
The United States Supreme Court has held that the First 
Amendment guarantees all citizens access to judicial proceedings. 
See Richmond Newspapers, Inc. v. Virginia, 448 U.S. 555, 582, 
100  S.Ct. 2814, 65 L.Ed.2d 973 (1980) (the courtroom "is a public 
place where the people generally--and representatives of the 
media--have a right to be present.").  
 
In Globe Newspaper Co. v. Superior Court, the court reiterated the 
Richmond decision, holding that when the public and press is 
excluded from a judicial proceeding, "it must be shown that the 
denial is necessitated by a completing governmental interest, and is 
narrowly tailored to serve that interest." Globe, supra p. 607. 
Richmond and Globe acknowledge the fundamental principle that: 
"What transpires in the courtroom is public property." Richmond, 
supra p. 583, n.9 [quoting Craig v. Harney, 331 U.S. 367, 374 
(1947), 67 S.Ct. 1249, 91 L.Ed 1546 (1947)]. An essential 
principle of our Constitution is:  
 
" . . . the common understanding [is] that "a major purpose of [the 
First]  Amendment was to protect the free discussion of public 
affairs." by  offering  such protection, the First Amendment serves 
to ensure that the individual citizen can effectively participate in 
and contribute to our republican system of self-government." 
(citations omitted)  
 
Globe, supra p. 604.  The First Amendment right of access to 
judicial  proceedings  "ensure[s] that [the] constitutionally 
protected 'discussion of governmental affairs' is an informed one." 
Globe, supra p. 605.  The guarantee of access "permits the public 
to participate in and serve as a check upon the judicial process-- an 
essential component in our structure of self-government." Globe, 
supra,p. 606. Further, when court proceedings have been concealed 
from public view an unexpected outcome can cause a reaction that 
the system at best has failed and at worst has been corrupted. 
Richmond, supra p. 571.  
 
This First Amendment right of access extends beyond the trial 
phase to other judicial proceedings. Press-Enterprise v. Riverside 
County  Superior Court,  478  U.S.  at  106 (access  extends  to 
preliminary proceedings in criminal cases).[fn 6] The First 
Amendment right of access extends to court records.  
 
"Throughout our history, the open courtroom has been a 
fundamental feature of the American judicial system. Basic 
principles have emerged to guide judicial discretion respecting 
public access to judicial proceedings. These principles apply as 
well to the determination of whether to permit access to 
information contained in court documents because court records 
often provide important, sometimes the only, bases or explanations 
for a court's decision."  
 
Brown & Williamson Tobacco Co. v. F.T.C., 710 F.2d at 1177. 
Thus, the United States Constitution imposes a heavy presumption 
that the judicial proceedings and records are open to the public and 
to the media as representatives of the media.  
 
There is a long-standing presumption in the common law that the 
public has  access to judicial records.   Nixon v. Warner 
Communications, Inc., 435 U.S. 589, 597 (1978); United States v. 
Rosenthal, 763 F.2d 1291, 1293 (11th Cir. 1985). This 
presumption of access can be rebutted only if countervailing 
interests "heavily outweigh the public interests in access."  
Rushford v. New Yorker Magazine, Inc.,  846 F.2d 249,  253  (4th 
Cir.  1988).   The party seeking to overcome the presumption of 
access bears the burden of showing some "significant interest" that 
outweighs the presumption.    
 
Further, following the U.5. Supreme Courts guidance on access to 
court proceedings, the courts have recognized that access to 
judicial records are also within the ambit of the First Amendment. 
In Brown, the Sixth Circuit vacated a suppression order that the 
district court had entered with regard to all documents filed by one 
of the parties, based on First Amendment and common law rights 
of access to judicial records. In so holding, the court found that 
"the First Amendment and the common law do limit judicial 
discretion" to seal court documents. Brown, supra, p. 1177. The 
Court went on to hold that the same constitutional and common 
law legal principles applicable to open courtrooms apply to a 
judicial file.  Id.  
 
Similarly, in Associated Press v. U.S. District Court for Cent. Dist. 
of Col., 705 F.2d 1143,  1145  (9th Cir.  1983),  the district court 
had prohibited public access to any of the pretrial documents filed 
in the federal prosecution of John De Lorean.  The Ninth Circuit 
reversed, and held that the public's right of access to these 
documents was based upon the First Amendment as well as the 
common law.  Accord Application of National Broadcasting Co., 
Inc., 828 F.2d 340 (6th Cir. 1987);  In Re San Juan Star Co., 662 
F.2d 108 (1st Cir. 1981); In the Matter of Continental Illinois 
Securities Litigation, 732 F.2d 1302 (7th Cir. 1984); United States 
v. Dorfman, 690 F.2d 1230 (7th Cir. 1982).  
 
In  short,  the  right  of  access  to  judicial records  is guaranteed 
both under the common law and by the United Stated Constitution 
and this presumptive right has not been overcome by appropriate 
findings that would justify closure.  
 
4.  Docket Sheet Should Reflect All Filings  
 
Even if all the documents now under seal were properly sealed 
based on a careful analysis, Media Group knows of no valid reason 
for maintaining dual docket sheets: one for the public and one for 
the parties. Docket sheets merely memorialize a very brief and 
encapsulated form of pleadings filed with the court. As argued 
hereinbefore, these filings (particularly in a criminal case) are 
presumptively open.  
 
Media Group cannot  conceive  of  a  situation where truly 
confidential matters could not be  filed under  seal with  the 
appropriate docket number and a brief description, (i.e., a caption 
from the pleading file), that would not fully protect whatever 
confidentiality has been found necessary. The docket entry could 
merely indicate that that document was filed under seal. In fact, the 
missing docket numbers are easily inferred from the sequential 
gaps. Thus, no purpose is presently being served by not having the 
docket entries entered sequentially. Again, a brief description or 
caption from the pleading can hardly be considered a breach of 
confidentiality.  It is very important for the public to have 
confidence in its court system and that confidence, at a minimum 
requires that every document filed is given a number and briefly 
described. It would even be more appropriate if some reference 
was made to the order authorizing the sealing. As the Eighth 
Circuit[fn 7] and the Eleventh Circuit has held,[fn 8] this dual 
docketing sheet system is contrary to the Constitution.  
 
5.   Current Nationwide Concern Has Heightened the Public's Need 
for Access.  
 
The Washington Post decision, which emphasizes one particular 
importance of public access to judicial documents related to the 
criminal justice system strikes an apropos chord in light of the  
anger and confusion still felt nationwide in the aftermath of the 
Oklahoma City bombing:   
 
"Violent crime has a profound impact upon societal well-being and 
often provokes public reactions of fear and outrage, as well as 
compassion for its victims. 'When the public is aware that the law 
is being enforced and the criminal justice system  is  functioning,  
an  outlet  is provided  for  these understandable reactions and 
emotions.'"  
 
Id. at 330 (quoting Press-Enterprise Co. v. Superior Court, 464 
U.S. at 509). The court further noted that releasing search warrant 
documents addresses the public's legitimate concerns about police 
methods and techniques as well as the public's right to be aware of  
crime patterns. Id. at 331. These concerns are magnified now, due 
to domestic terrorist atrocities such as the bombing of the World 
Trade Center and the Oklahoma City federal building. In addition, 
fears of continuing threats have been intensified by recent moves to 
increase security at the White House,other federal buildings and 
airports across the country.  In view of the current national 
sentiment, releasing the requested search warrant documents is not  
only justified, but mandated under the "public need" test set out by 
the Ninth Circuit in Times Mirror.   
 
At a Minimum, the Court Should Require Cause to be Shown 
and/or Release the Search Warrant Documents in Redacted Form.  
 
A court may deny public access to judicial proceedings and 
documents only "when sealing is 'essential to preserve higher 
values and is narrowly tailored to serve that interest.'" Baltimore 
Sun Co. v. Goetz, 886 F.2d 60, 65-66 (4th Cir. 1989) (quoting 
Press- Enterprise I, 464 U.S. at 510). Courts must consider 
alternatives to sealing documents, which "ordinarily involves 
disclosing some of the documents or giving access to a redacted 
version." Id. at 66. Thus, to the extent this court deems it necessary 
to keep certain portions of the search warrant documents under 
seal, it should release the documents with those portions redacted. 
See, e.g., In Re Search Warrants, 18 Med.L.Rep. 1095, 1100 
(D.D.C. 1990) (permitting the release of search warrant affidavits  
in redacted form to protect the privacy rights of innocent third 
parties).  
 
RELIEF REQUESTED 
 
For the foregoing reasons, the court should grant petitioners' 
motion and order that: (1) the public shall have immediate access 
to all sealed documents,(2) the court clerk is to provide immediate 
public access to the complete docket sheets in these cases, and (3) 
hereafter petitioners are to receive notice of motions to seal 
documents and be given an opportunity to object before those 
motions are considered. Alternatively, the Court should order the 
parties to show cause why sealed documents should remain sealed 
and, absent the necessary showing,unseal the documents or provide 
public access to  redacted versions of the documents where 
appropriate.  
 
MICHAEL MINNIS & ASSOCIATES, P.C. 
 
/s/ Michael Minnis, OBA #6251 
David McCullough, OBA #10898 
3160 Liberty Tower 
100 North Broadway 
Oklahoma City, OK  73102 
(405) 235-7686 
 
ATTORNEYS FOR MEDIA GROUP    
 
 
CERTIFICATE OF SERVICE 
 
